<HEAD>One Year After Quake, Leninakan Mired in Mud and Memories</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LENINAKAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A year after an earthquake smashed northwestern <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> into rubble, the city of <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> is a shantytown of mud and memories. The Garapetyans do laundry by boiling their clothes in a bucket on a tiny wood stove. The stove also heats a makeshift cabin they built from remains of their former apartment building next door. Far above, rain lashes the wallpaper of their old living room on the fourth floor, which was exposed when the side of the building sheared off. `` We're afraid of living in a large building again,'' <PERSON> Meruzhan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garapetyan </PERSON> said. Popular songs speak of the disaster of Dec. 7, 1988, when an earthquake measuring 6.9 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale killed at least 25,000 people and destroyed the homes of 500,000 more. `` Oh earthquake, what have you done?'' one asks. `` Why did you leave so many parents without their children? ... You covered them with stones and dirt and left their parents in tears.'' The Armenian relief agency Search says 20,000 people still are missing, 2,000 of them children. Daily life is slogging through mud, relying on relatives and wondering when normality will return. A quake of 7.1 magnitude in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> area on Oct. 17 killed only 66 people. Damage was estimated at $ 7 billion, but much of the destruction was cleared and service restored within weeks. In <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s second-largest city, <PERSON> Vartan </PERSON> <PERSON> Oganisyan </PERSON> and his family of five live in a shack made from bits of sheet metal, wood scraps, tar paper and salvaged window frames. Other families crowd into half-shattered buildings, construction huts, army tents, round Mongolian yurts, abandoned railway cars and even gasoline tanks fitted with doors and windows. A few open cooking fires can be seen in the twilight. Electrical power is intermittent as <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> enters the bitter Soviet winter. Children bundle up for classes in temporary, unheated buildings. They wake up crying at night and run from classrooms in fright at the slightest noise. After school they play `` earthquake,'' recreating the disaster in the muddy streets. Hundreds of people go to the huge city cemetery after work. Many graves are marked only by the flowers relatives leave. <PERSON> Sofik </PERSON> <PERSON> Torunyan </PERSON>, who lost both children, was there on what would have been her daughter's 20th birthday, with a cake fashioned from carnations. `` Oh, my young daughter! Oh, my love!'' she wailed, holding onto a friend. `` Why did n't I die, too, so I would not have to live without you?'' People struggle on, helping each other. Hospitality and pride remain. A dozen families share the only bathroom on their block that still works. A boy paints the window frame in his family's shack. Visitors are offered coffee and sweets, but often there is no electricity to boil water. <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Tumanyan </PERSON>, who lives in the ground floor of a severely cracked five-story building, insists that `` we're making great progress.'' She concentrates on the vast stretches cleared of broken concrete and twisted metal, not the rubble remaining. The town of <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION> was leveled. Kirovakan and 300 villages were shattered. In <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>, which had 235,000 residents, the quake destroyed 99 nine-story apartment buildings, 10 schools and every factory, officials said. Reconstruction has lagged badly. <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>, the Soviet premier, said in November that the crash program to rebuild in two years already was a year behind schedule, meaning virtually nothing had been accomplished. Residents blame disorganization, central planning's failure to supply enough building materials and a two-month blockade of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> by ethnic enemies in neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. Many foreigners building schools and hospitals went home because supply shipments were held up on rail lines in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. By early November, only three new buildings had been completed, all by the army for the army. <PERSON> Karlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ambartsumyan </PERSON>, chairman of the city <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> committee, still hopes to move 4,000 families into a vast new suburb before year's end, but even that would be only one-fifth as many as planned. For now, <PERSON> Ambartsumyan </PERSON> is concentrating on getting the remaining homeless among the 190,000 people now living in <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> into construction huts and other temporary housing, and getting heat for them before winter. <PERSON> Svetlana </PERSON> <PERSON> Asaturyan </PERSON> lives in one such hut, generously called a `` little house'' in Russian but in reality a two-room insulated packing crate. She and her family of five must haul water from a block away, use nearby bushes as a toilet and travel to a relative's place for showers. Her washing flaps over a sea of mud. Mrs. <PERSON> Asaturyan </PERSON> is grateful, however, because they used to be in the remains of the towel factory where she once worked, and where 30 of her co-workers were killed. Her `` little house,'' like thousands of others, showed up without a door, window glass, heater, wiring or furniture. It was vandalized en route, apparently by <PERSON> Azerbaijanis </PERSON>, whom the Armenians accuse of stealing or destroying relief supplies. When asked about the Soviet leadership's promise to rebuild in two years, Mrs. <PERSON> Asaturyan </PERSON> said: `` I'll be glad if I get a home within five years.'' About 20,000 of the homeless are scheduled to receive apartments in the new suburb as sections are completed over 18 months. A forest of 129 cranes towers over the site, and buildings faced with local salmon-colored stone gleam in the sun. Because nine-story apartment blocks shoddily built of pre-formed concrete panels collapsed in the quake, the new buildings are made by assembling vault-like precast rooms, foreman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> Pogosov </PERSON> said. None is more than four stories high. In May, a commission of the ruling Politburo blamed most of the deaths on shoddy construction and gave its findings to prosecutors. No charges have been filed, said <PERSON> Haik </PERSON> <PERSON> Minasyan </PERSON>, an Armenian government spokesman. Only a few projects are under way in the city itself. On the central square, a statue of <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> looks over a scene of devastation: a ruined school, department store, government building, post office, shops and a sock factory. Cafes and movie theaters are gone. So are most food stores, and shopping sometimes amounts to picking over piles of cabbages and potatoes at what remains of the bus station. <PERSON> Ambartsumyan </PERSON> said experts had ruled out reconstruction on half the original city lots because the ground is too unstable.
