<SECOND>PM-Confession Controversy,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man at Center of Church-State Debate Pleads Guilty</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY SPRINGS, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A showdown between three Pentecostal ministers and a prosecutor over the confidentiality of a burglary suspect's confession in church ended when the man pleaded guilty to grand larceny. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Yost </PERSON>, who was to have gone on trial today, entered the plea Monday under an agreement reached at a hearing before <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Steptoe </PERSON>. <PERSON> Yost </PERSON>, 35, had been charged with the more serious crime of breaking and entering. `` It's over with,'' said a jubilant Rev. <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiles </PERSON>. `` We do n't have to testify, nor do we have to refuse to testify.'' <PERSON> Yost </PERSON>'s hearing came after <PERSON> Steptoe </PERSON> refused for the second time to excuse Mrs. <PERSON> Hiles </PERSON>, 51; her husband, the Rev. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiles </PERSON>, the 58-year-old founder and pastor of the <ORGANIZATION> Word </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deliverance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>; and the Rev. <PERSON> Wilda </PERSON> <PERSON> Maconaughey </PERSON> from subpoenas issued by county Prosecutor <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> IV. <PERSON> Yost </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> carpenter who has been held at the Eastern Regional Jail in lieu of $ 15,000 bond since January, was sentenced to a year in the county jail, with credit for time served. `` I'm happy, the whole church is happy,'' <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from jail. `` I did n't want to see the ministers go to jail. And I should be out in a month if everything goes right.'' Last December, a sobbing <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> interrupted a service at the church, confessing that he did n't try to stop the break-in at his uncle's building supply store. The ministers had said <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> wanted them to testify at <PERSON> Yost </PERSON>'s trial, and maintained authorities had crossed the boundary between God's work and their own <PERSON> Steptoe </PERSON> first refused to block the subpoenas Nov. 15, ruling that state law does not protect confessions made to clergy. The state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last week refused to hear the ministers' challenge <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> are the only states that do not protect confessions made to ministers or priests in criminal cases, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gay </PERSON>, the ministers' lawyer. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, however, does allow statements made to clergy about divorce proceedings to be kept secret, <PERSON> Gay </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> said earlier that just before Christmas he told the congregation that he watched and did nothing as another man broke into his uncle's store last December. He denied having a role in the robbery. `` It was such a burden on my heart, I just had to go to my church and get it off my chest,'' <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> said. Gay said another attorney has contacted him about drafting legislation to protect clergy and penitents in similar situations. `` I was disappointed the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> did n't take this opportunity to examine the issue,'' he said. `` It's a fundamental issue that cries out to be heard.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution provides for freedom of religion. Gay also argued that the state constitution prohibits anyone from being subpoenaed, jailed or arrested based upon a religious belief. The importance of protecting confessions made to clergy has been recognized since the days of the Roman Empire, accordi