<HEAD>Gorbachev Challenge: To Lead Way to New Political Alliance</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> sets out from his first superpower summit meeting with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to lead his <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact alliance into a new era of cooperation with the West _ or risk being left behind and alone. As he and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> parted after two days in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> headed home for a meeting with a dramatically different and more Westward-looking <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> leadership than when members last convened in July. The communist bloc alliance has become less communist and less a bloc, presenting <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> with the challenge of leading the transition he described from a Kremlin-dominated military alliance to a new political association guiding <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in its rush to erase the lines that have divided East and West for 45 years. Culturally and geographically, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> partners are closer to the West than the vast <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> straddling <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. And as they turn away from the Kremlin to face the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> may find it increasingly difficult to drive his stubbornly backward society at a quick enough pace to catch up. At his joint news conference with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> closing their first summit meeting, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> declared himself `` encouraged and inspired'' by the changes that have swept hardline communists from power in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>. The changes, he said, show `` the desire of these peoples to ennoble their societies, to make them more democratic and humanitarian and to open up to the rest of the world.'' But they also dramatically alter the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION>'s once dominant and domineering role in the alliance. For the first time since the pact was signed in the Polish capital in 1955 in response to the formation of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, one of the leaders present _ Polish Prime Minister <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> _ will be a non-communist. <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>, a leader of the independent Solidarity labor movement suppressed with Soviet support in 1981, was elected in August to head <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s first non-communist government in four decades. And on the eve of the summit, the leadership of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, at the heart of the strategic alliance, was wrenched by its second spasm in recent weeks as communist leader <PERSON> Egon </PERSON> <PERSON> Krenz </PERSON> and the party's entire top echelon abdicated to a 25-member panel of reformers in a desperate effort to salvage some measure of support for the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Krenz </ORGANIZATION> relinquished the party post he had held less than six weeks, and although he retained the largely ceremonial title of president, it was not immediately clear who would represent <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> at the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> meeting. Several other East European leaders, including <PERSON> Petar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mladenov </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Karel </PERSON> <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, are attending their first <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact leadership meeting. And for the first time since the alliance was formed, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, now out of power, apparently was n't invited at all <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>, who continues to rule <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> with the iron hand once rewarded by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, is the only <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc leader who rejects the democratically inspired reform movement. With the recent fall of orthodox communist leaders like <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Honecker </PERSON> in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, he is likely to find himself more isolated than ever as he sits down with the new generation of East European leaders.
</TEXT>
