<HEAD>Summit Offers Cure for Country With Identity Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALLETTA, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Before the dockside summit, this tiny island nation suffered from an identity crisis. Maltese passports even included a map to show doubtful foreigners that the country exists. But that was before President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> came to <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> and put this rocky <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> archipelago back on everyone's map. The passports will be changed shortly after the first of the year, said a slightly embarrassed <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Cachia </PERSON> <PERSON> Caruana </PERSON>, the aide to the prime minister who was in charge of organizing <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>'s part in the summit. `` That was a lack of self-confidence by the previous government,'' he said, shaking his head. `` It's degrading.'' Any lingering doubts by the Maltese about their country's identity seemed to have been dispelled by the superpower summit, by the words and images beamed abroad by about 2,500 journalists covering the <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush-Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> talks `` For <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> itself, the summit has been very positive. It has shown <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> can cope even with the necessary organization for a summit like this,'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Fenech </PERSON> <PERSON> Adami </PERSON> said in an interview after the summit closed Sunday. `` Some people were skeptical that <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> could do it. I think we proved ourselves,'' he added. Not even the fierce December gale that drove the summit at sea to the side of a pier could dampen the enthusiasm of the prime minister. `` Well, I do n't mind the weather at all. If anything, it has proved I was correct when I suggested that the meetings should not be held in <LOCATION> Marsaxlokk </LOCATION> but in some other bay, such as <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, which is more protected than <PERSON> Marsaxlokk </PERSON> <PERSON> Bay </PERSON>,'' he said. <PERSON> Cachia </PERSON> <PERSON> Caruana </PERSON> said the Soviets and Americans first planned to hold the summit at sea, perhaps in Maltese territorial waters, but that the prime minister had convinced them of the hazards of December. `` Within 24 hours we made the point that this is December and that these things can happen,'' he said. Still, he acknowledges the images of thunderous waves crashing against the rocks below the 16th Century fortifications of the capital <LOCATION> Valletta </LOCATION> wo n't help the island's winter tourism. `` In terms of what we had hoped to achieve overall, the tourism objectives probably will not be met,'' said <PERSON> Cachia </PERSON> <PERSON> Caruana </PERSON>. `` But our principal objective, especially in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, was name identification. `` Just being at the center of the world stage for two days in a way helped give us that anyway.'' <PERSON> Cachia </PERSON> <PERSON> Caruana </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> wants to base its growth on business, not just tourism, and that's why the summit will help. `` Our greatest objective is dragging the economy into the last decade of the 20th Century,'' he said. Still, in those first few hours after the departure of the leaders of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the chief Maltese organizer of the summit was relieved that it was over. `` It's been a hell of an experience. We had a situation here where the journalists outnumbered the army by two-to-one,'' said <PERSON> Cachia </PERSON> <PERSON> Caruana </PERSON>. `` It's back to business as usual tomorrow. We will assume it was a dream and forget all about it.''
</TEXT>
