<HEAD>Seven Referendums on North Dakota Ballot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE WETZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakotans </LOCATION> take a tradition of political orneriness to the polls Tuesday in a special election that will decide seven referendums, including higher taxes, gambling and sex education. The debate has focused on whether to sustain the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to raise taxes on income, sales and gasoline, a move opponents contend will drive people and businesses out of a state already in an economic slump It also has pitted gambling opponents against the attorney general, and the state health department against a parents' group troubled by proposed mandatory health instruction in the public schools. `` It's certainly been a difficult campaign,'' said Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinner </PERSON>, who has held dozens of public forums urging voters to uphold the tax increases. Over the years, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> voters have used referendums to block construction of a state office building, reverse a college name change and sustain a ban on municipal parking meters. However, they have n't had to vote on so many referendums at one time since June 1919, when voters approved seven bills, said Secretary of State <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kusler </PERSON>. One established the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dakota </ORGANIZATION>, which remains the nation's only state-owned bank. Sinner, a Democrat, won his second term last year with 60 percent of the vote against a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate who pledged not to raise taxes. This fall, he threw himself into the lead role of campaigning for the tax bills that would raise the sales tax from 5 percent to 6 percent; the gasoline tax from 17 cents to 20 cents a gallon; and the income tax from 14 percent to 17 percent of a taxpayer's federal tax bill `` If I do n't keep this state with a good future, I'm going to consider my job and my work as a failure. Nothing else seems to me to be any more important than that, and politics be damned,'' Sinner told reporters. The governor has used the specter of increased property taxes and drastic cuts in education and social services if voters reject the tax measures. Last week in <LOCATION> Bismarck </LOCATION>, he appeared on stage with two men in wheelchairs, who spoke about their fears of cuts in state human-services spending. Kent French, a <LOCATION> Bismarck </LOCATION> businessman who has led the fight against the tax increases, says the governor is exaggerating their possible impact. `` It's time for state government to make spending choices, the same way families have had to do,'' French said. `` Their choice has been to raise taxes, and that's got to stop.'' In addition to the three separate referendums on taxes, voters must decide whether to approve the sex education issue, a mandatory seat-belt law, a retirement program for legislators and legalization of video gambling machines. They also were considering a proposed constitutional amendment to reorganize state government. Attorney General <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Spaeth </PERSON> is advocating the gambling machines as an honest alternative to pull tabs _ pull-apart paper tickets that players draw at random from a jar in hopes of picking one carrying a cash prize. But introduction of the machines is being fought by opponents of state-sanctioned gambling, including former Gov. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Link </PERSON>, and pull tab manufacturers who fear the machines will cut into their market. `` It certainly has n't been a political success for me to endorse the concept of electronic gaming. But I think it's the right thing for <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Spaeth </PERSON> said last week. Debate over the health curriculum has centered on whether information about AIDS and other sexually transmitted diseases belongs in public schools. The law under challenge in the referendum would mandate health education in every school, including information about sexually transmitted diseases. It leaves decisions on details largely to individual districts. An opponent, <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergstedt </PERSON>, a registered nurse from the western <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> community of <PERSON> Hazen </PERSON>, contends the teaching of sexual abstinence should take precedence over instruction on the use of contraceptives as a way of preventing disease. `` The opponents are looking for bogymen under every stone,'' countered Dr. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonough </PERSON>, an official of the state health department. He said the education program will emphasize abstinence. Polls indicate voters are leaning in favor of the seat belt and health education laws but against electronic gambling and the legislative retirement program. The polls initially showed overwhelming opposition to the tax increases, but they have shifted in favor of tax advocates as the election nears, and both sides predict a close result. `` It's going to go right down to the wire,'' French said. `` I just pray to God it does n't snow on December Fifth.''
