<HEAD>AMA Executive Admits Errors in Financial Flap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON STATON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s top executive said he made mistakes in approving two money-losing internal financial deals, but denied that the resulting controversy spurred him to retire. `` I accept responsibility for the errors and the changes that are needed to prevent their recurrence,'' <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> Executive Vice President Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> told the opening ceremony of the group's mid-year meeting. <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> and Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. Ring, chairman of the board of trustees, said in speeches to the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON>' plans to retire at the end of his current contract were known months ago. The 425 delegates are meeting through Wednesday to set <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> policy on numerous national health-care issues, but the internal financial controversy has captured much of their attention. The Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> is the nation's largest organization for doctors, with nearly 300,000 members. The controversy centers on revelations this fall that <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> approved a $ 353,000 reimbursement to a former <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> executive for losses in a 1987 high-risk stock market fund, and a 1985 loan to another <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> executive to buy a high-price condominium during the latter's divorce. The executive involved in the stock-market loss has promised to pay back the money with interest. The recipient of the 1985 loan later defaulted, costing the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> $ 50,000 to foreclose. Ring told the delegates an investigation is continuing and a full report will be made to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION>. He said the board would take steps so that `` this will not happen again.'' The board on Saturday issued a report saying <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> acted within his authority in the two deals, but `` failed to follow the usual fiscal policies and procedures.'' <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> said trustees declined to elaborate. The board also said it had accepted <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON>' plan to retire, effective March 31, 1991. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> said it was unclear why the board had included the retirement plans in the report on the deals. <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON>, who is widely respected for rescuing the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> from financial disaster when he took the job in 1974, plans to give up day-to-day management of the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> at the end of next year. The board report also proposed a restructuring of its committees and hiring of an outside accounting firm. It said the board would set tighter fiscal limits on the authority of the executive vice president, but did not elaborate. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION> also will consider a resolution passed last month by the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> urging <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> be placed on administrative leave until the investigation is completed. On Sunday, Secretary of Education <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> asked the physicians for help in improving and restructuring the nation's education system He asked the physicians to help raise public awareness of the nation's educational shortcomings. During the meetings, the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> delegates also will consider reports and resolutions that would: _ Acknowledge a patient's right to basic and essential health care; _ Establish policies regarding `` maternal-fetal conflict,'' such as when an expectant mother refuses medical treatment that would benefit her fetus; _ Encourage health-insurance companies to develop reduced-cost coverage for non-smokers; _ Urge a lowering of the blood-alcohol level to 0.05 percent for determination of drunken driving;. _ Work toward listing tobacco as a contributing factor on death certificates.
