<HEAD>U.S. Attorney Probes Dinkins Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor-elect <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> said he was not worried by a federal probe into a stock transfer to his son, said to be part of a larger investigation into a cable television franchise. `` I'm confident this inquiry will reveal that there's nothing with which I need to be concerned,'' <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> said Sunday. `` Those of us in public life are subject to criticism and scrutiny of all sorts over time.'' <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> said the investigation stems from a suggestion by his defeated opponent in the Nov. 7 mayoral election, Republican <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>, who said during the campaign that the stock deal should be examined. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Stillman </PERSON>, an attorney for <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>, described the federal investigation as `` <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>'s last hurrah.'' <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> is the former <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney. The <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday that <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney based in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, is investigating the transaction of stock by <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> to his son, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. Investigators are trying to determine whether <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> transferred <ORGANIZATION> Inner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> stock to his son through a genuine transaction in 1985, how much the stock was worth and whether all due taxes were paid, the News reported Inner City owns several radio stations and one of its subsidiaries has a substantial interest in <ORGANIZATION> Queens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Innerunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION>, a cable franchise. Inner City's chairman, former <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> Borough President <PERSON> Percy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON>, is a longtime friend of <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> has said he first acquired stock in the privately held company in 1972 and his holdings grew to 588 shares, largely through stock splits. After his election as <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> borough president in 1985, <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> said, he began transferring the stock to his son to avoid a conflict between his position on the city <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estimate </ORGANIZATION> and the board's role in regulating cable television. <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Driscoll </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney, characterized the investigation as a `` preliminary inquiry into some financial transactions.'' She refused to elaborate. During the campaign, it was revealed that <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> had not paid a gift tax. <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> released a handwritten note, dated Oct. 30, 1985, in which his son agreed to buy the stock. But <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> declined to release financial or corporate records that might further document the transaction. As part of the investigation, the News said, the age of the paper and ink are being tested to determine whether the note was written in 1985 or during the campaign. There also are plans to analyze the handwriting, the newspaper said. The city's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION> is conducting a separate, previously disclosed probe into whether <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> filed misleading financial disclosure forms pertaining to the stock.
