<HEAD>Survey Finds Sexual Harassment in Large U.S. Law Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sexual harassment and limited opportunity for advancement are part of a woman's work environment at large <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law firms, a study says. The survey, published in today's edition of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>, was based on responses from 918 women lawyers who work in large law firms in 13 cities. Most women said they were at a disadvantage when it came to advancement. Sixty-four percent said men had a better chance at gaining management positions and 49 percent said men were more likely to be promoted. According to the survey, 60 percent of respondents said they had experienced unwanted sexual attention, such as sexual teasing, remarks or questions, from co-workers or clients. Nearly one-third said they had experienced sexual looks or gestures. The lawyers who responded to the survey earned between $ 50,000 and $ 250,000 a year. Thirteen percent said they felt their male counterparts earned higher salaries and bigger bonuses. The majority of the women felt they had to give up time for family, friends or outside interests to pursue their law careers, but they indicated that male lawyers made the same sacrifices. The survey participants worked in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>. The survey was conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> and West Publishing of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, the nation's largest publisher of legal publications.
