<HEAD>Party Down And Out, Hoping For Reincarnation In Face of Renewed Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ONDREJ HEJMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Its monopoly on power gone, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is on the run, looking desperately for new strength in the forthcoming political battle for control. Communists were the vanguard of reform during the ill-fated `` Prague Spring'' under <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> until the spontaneous freedom movement was squelched by Soviet tanks in 1968. But new forces seem to be in charge this time around. `` The future requires giving up the monopoly of power,'' new party leader <PERSON> Karel </PERSON> <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON> said last week. A 77-year-old veteran Communist says it's `` hard to foresee any kind of real political comeback for the party, now that the lies and incompetence are here for everyone to see, hear and read about. The man, requesting anonymity, said `` only a miracle'' can save the Communist leadership from collapse now that the 2-week-old peaceful popular revolt has shaken it to the core. In a stormy party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commitee </ORGANIZATION> meeting Nov. 24, former premier <PERSON> Lubomir </PERSON> <PERSON> Strougal </PERSON> called the demonstrations `` an expression of civil dissatisfaction with us, our way of leadership and rule.'' `` Let us admit our share of responsibility,'' the party daily <PERSON> Rude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pravo </PERSON> quoted him as saying. Days later, the party decided to revise its stand on the 1968 <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> invasion, part of its speedy move to jettison the leaders and policies of the last 21 years. Those aging party members, who carried the torch of `` real socialism'' from the 1948 Communist takeover until November 1989, have been spared a younger Communist generation's worries about the party's future. `` I'm of the opinion that the entire <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> should be disbanded and possibly associate under a different name, if we find the right program and people willing to do it,'' <PERSON> Vit </PERSON> <PERSON> Spanhel </PERSON>, 43, a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> journalist, told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. That has already happened in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, where the unpopular <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> dissolved itself last month and christened a new ruling party _ the Socialists _ as part of its attempt to save itself from overwhelming defeat in free elections next year. With a membership of 1.7 million _ roughly one in every six Czechoslovak adults is a Communist _ the party is still the best organized political force in the country. It may be hit by massive defections now that its power is eroded. But it still has control of thousands of offices and factories and many of the people who run them. <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, the country's leading dissident and the unofficial leader of the Civic Forum opposition coalition, says that by comparison his group is composed of `` political amateurs.'' The country's <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, formerly docile <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> allies, have now begun to flourish in the new atmosphere of free speech. Membership applications are pouring in, but both parties still remain comparatively tiny forces of less than 50,000 members. A broad spectrum of several independent parties, similar to that in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, is expected to emerge before free elections take place, probably late next year. Czechoslovak wits are beginning to mourn the easy target they found in the Communists for 40 years. Hinting at the clumsiness of former leader <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> and the depressing obscurity of the new communist chief, the writing on the subway wall said last week: `` Milos, come back, <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON> is no fun!''
