<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS-ARRIVE 1stLd-Writethru a0423 12-04 0868</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-ARRIVE, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0423,0891</SECOND>
<HEAD>Program Targets Ex-Cons, Ex-Drug Abusers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf, `Sometimes the ...' with two grafs to CLARIFY
that 37 percent dropout rate was for first five groups of students; This
story is part of a continuing series, `AIDS Update'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 ARRIVE is a school that pays students $ 10 just to show up, but there are two requirements for admission: recent release from jail and a history of intravenous drug abuse. The program works to develop a social-services network to help its students get back into society _ and get what they need if they develop AIDS. `` The primary purpose of the program is to stop the transmission -LRB- of AIDS -RRB-, but to do that you have to help people get their lives together,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wexler </PERSON>, program director for ARRIVE _ a loose acronym for AIDS Risk Reduction and Education for Former Intravenous Drug Abusers Entering Society. Still, ARRIVE classes, which meet three nights a week, cover far more than AIDS awareness. `` I want us to quickly identify some of the things that stress us out,'' Clinical Director <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Josepher </PERSON> told a class of about 25 people, mostly black men, who had gathered one night in a Lower <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> office building. `` Trying to deal with life now without the use of drugs,'' responded one man with a graying goatee. `` It has been so long.'' `` Dealing with your children when they're young,'' said another, to a chorus of agreement. `` Dealing with a crack son,'' said a woman. In the beginning, few women enrolled. Now one of the 24 classes deals specifically with women and AIDS. In the early days, the cookies did n't last through the evening; the organizers learned some students had nothing else to eat. At least one showed up directly from jail, suitcase in hand. ARRIVE has evolved in another way, too. It has become something of an advocacy force for a high-risk population without a voice. Since the start of 1988, intravenous drug users have accounted for more of the AIDS cases reported in the city than any other group. In an anonymous random sampling, about 35 percent of state prison inmates tested HIV-positive. ARRIVE helps students draw up resumes and look for jobs, especially in drug and AIDS counseling. It gives out subway tokens, and offers a 24-hour source of support, even to those who return to drugs. `` We have to deal with the fact that they're going to experiment and they will be pulled back into old behaviors,'' said <PERSON> Josepher </PERSON>. Sometimes the streets win. Thirty-seven percent of those who entered ARRIVE did n't graduate, according to figures from its first five groups of students. Dropout figures are n't available for its two most recent groups, including one that graduated Friday. Some graduates get stipends to help others through the program. In August, one helper was shot to death in <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>. Many students left jail to find the streets changed _ filled with younger faces and more violence revolving around crack. `` I've gotten a lot of feedback from our students that they feel like outsiders,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, an ARRIVE trainer. `` Producing a lot of discomfort for people who've had a history of substance abuse will drive them back to the drug.'' Those who stick it out are often people who've shown their strength before. <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> got himself off speedballs, a mixture of heroin and cocaine, at age 24. At 30, he was ordered imprisoned for nine years for manslaughter; once inside, he sent himself back to school. Now, he works for <ORGANIZATION> Narcotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which runs ARRIVE, going to prisons to recruit prospective students. He lives with a sister who's on crack. His brother is an intravenous drug user. `` I knew that I would either come back out here and be part of the problem or part of the solution,'' <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Melendez </PERSON>, 35, freed herself from a whirlpool of cocaine, alcohol and compulsive gambling. `` I used to gamble my food stamps,'' she said. She joined ARRIVE with her husband, who is in a drug-rehabilitation program. At home, she tells their six children, ages 4 months to 16 years, what she learns at ARRIVE. `` I want to go to school and teach children about AIDS,'' she said. `` I want to spread what I learned.'' ARRIVE is funded by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION>, and the students are part of an experiment that will compare them with other ex-cons who get less treatment or no treatment at all. All told, a research subject can earn $ 280 for completing the program. It's enough to bring people in but not enough to keep them, says <PERSON> Wexler </PERSON>. `` People who do n't get motivated, who do n't get connected, they just leave.'' It helps that the teachers know well where the students have been. <PERSON> Josepher </PERSON> says he and <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> spent time in jail and used drugs. `` One of the main problems in the beginning is imparting to them visions of hope,'' said <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>. `` I've got to teach them about self-respect,'' said <PERSON> Josepher </PERSON>. `` I've got to help them to see that they're self-destructive and this translates into anger directed at themselves.''
</TEXT>
