<HEAD>Report: More Than a Third of U.S. Hospitals Fail Quality Standards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hospital patients face a greater risk of infection or inappropriate surgery because many hospitals are n't meeting quality standards, according to the head of a group that monitors health-care facilities More than a third of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hospitals failed to meet quality standards designed to guard against inappropriate surgery, unnecessary blood transfusions and poorly coordinated treatment in special coronary and intensive-care units, according to a report in Sunday's <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>. The report also found that more than 40 percent of hospitals were cited for violations of safety standards, ranging from inadequate electrical wiring to improper disposal of hazardous waste. The report was based on surveys of 5,208 facilities collected from 1986 to 1988 by the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accreditation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Healthcare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organizations </ORGANIZATION>, which sets quality standards for health-care facilities. The Chicago-based commission said it had not analyzed the data to determine how many violations were major. But the commission's president, Dr. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> O </PERSON> <PERSON> ` </PERSON> <PERSON> Leary </PERSON>, said, `` Compliance problems mean that there is a greater risk of a bad outcome, such as infection in the hospital, or a transfusion reaction or a surgical misadventure. `` We consider that to be serious,'' he said. <PERSON> O'Leary </PERSON> said more and more hospitals are letting their buildings run down because of financial pressures. `` Do hospitals have adequate resources to really comply with the standards? Maybe not,'' <PERSON> O'Leary </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> reported that the commission found that: _ Fifty-one percent of hospitals did not have adequate procedures for reviewing surgery to determine whether it should have been done and whether it was done correctly _ Fifty-six percent did not properly monitor and evaluate how well the medical staff in different departments gave care _ Fifty percent did not properly monitor what happened to patients in special intensive-care and coronary-care units _ Thirty-five percent did not always review blood transfusion procedures to determine whether a patient needed a transfusion and whether whole blood or blood components should have been used Blood components carry less risk of infection from viruses that can not be detected by current screening tests, such as hepatitis C. About five-sixths of the nation's hospitals are surveyed by the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, whose seal of approval qualifies them to get Medicare and Medicaid reimbursements without an extra government inspection. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bader </PERSON>, a quality consultant based in <LOCATION> Rockville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, said the pattern of problems indicated that physicians are increasingly reluctant to review each other's care in the hospital, either because of the time required or the fear of lawsuits. That does n't mean patients are getting poor care, only that hospitals often are uninformed about what kind of care they are giving, <PERSON> Bader </PERSON> said. Dr. <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, director of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, D.C.-based <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, said the commission should publicly disclose its compliance data for individual hospitals. `` If you're going to be a regulatory agency, you have to let the public know what you're finding,'' <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> said.
