<HEAD>Airport Foes Clash With Police at Planned Construction Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of a radical leftist group hurled firebombs and stones today at riot police trying to remove huts built illegally on the site of a proposed new runway at <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s international airport, police said Police fought back with water cannons, but there were no reports of injuries, said an offical of the <ORGANIZATION> Chiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prefectural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. The official said <PERSON> Masaaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Komurasaki </PERSON>, a 27-year-old member of the Battle Flag leftist group, was arrested for allegedly constructing a tower on the construction site. About five people atop the tower, which was several yards high, threw firebombs and stones as riot police moved in with bulldozers and backhoes to get rid of about 10 huts built inside and near the site of the planned runway, officials said. Local farmers and their supporters, including radicals seizing on the issue for their anti-government activities, have been resisting the government's plans to expropriate farmland to expand the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION>, which opened in 1978 with just one runway. Complaints of congestion have been growing, and the government plans to complete construction of another 8,250-foot runway within next year. Today marked the start of police action to clear the huts. The official said 5,000 riot police were mobilized to block off the area. Another 1,500 riot police are to be mobilized to strengthen checkpoints on roads leading to the airport, he added. About 230 opponents, including members of the Chukakuha, another radical group opposed to the airport, are living in huts and other structures there, police sources said. The <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> says eight farmers still live inside the planned expansion site. Transport Minister <PERSON> Takami </PERSON> <PERSON> Eto </PERSON> told a news conference he had apologized to local farmers for the government's choosing <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> as the airport site, ministry officials said. <PERSON> Eto </PERSON> said his apology was contained in a letter mailed Saturday in reply to a protest letter sent by some farmers. <PERSON> Eto </PERSON>, the first transport minister to make such an official apology to farmers, said he would like to have talks with farmers opposing the airport, the officials added.
