<HEAD>Who's Hot, Who's Not _ That's the Question for Who's Who Editors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Once someone...' to add that people sometimes
are dropped from book at their request, add attribution.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMETTE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Who's a Who? That's the question the editors of `` Who's Who in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'' must decide as they prepare listings for the 1990-91 edition of the reference book. Actor <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> will be listed in the new Who's Who. But Mr. T, star of the canceled `` A-Team'' TV series, will not be. Baseball slugger <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Canseco </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A </ORGANIZATION>'s is a Who, but <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> rookie of the year, <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Walton </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION> centerfielder, is not. `` <PERSON> Walton </PERSON> was rookie of the year, true,'' explained <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>, product manager for Who's Who In <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` But you do n't know What about his sophomore year? What if he fizzles?'' Once someone is listed, it's for life, until retirement, until someone asks to be left out or until conviction for a serious crime, <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said. Sometimes the editors look the other way at a conviction, as in the case of Watergate convicts <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ehrlichman </PERSON>, H.R. <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Colson </PERSON>, who continue to be listed. Thousands of questionnaires were mailed this fall from Who's Who headquarters in this northern <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb to Nobel laureates, federal judges, movie stars, Fortune 500 company officials, newspaper editors, junior partners in major accounting firms, up-and-coming lawyers, and others. Researchers at the headquarters comb through newspapers, magazines and corporate reports for prospective listees. `` We try to be as objective as we can be in our standards,'' <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said. `` We try to quantify quality.'' Those who return the questionnaires, providing information about their accomplishments, memberships, education and the like, are guaranteed a place among the 79,000 people to be listed in the new edition, due out in September 1990. <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said the expected return rate is only 12 percent to 14 percent. Years ago, as many as 20 percent returned the questionnaires. He said the rate has dropped because people are confused by the proliferation of such books _ many of them vanity press publications that charge for a listing. In contrast, `` Who's Who in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' a publication of <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, makes clear in its preface that its entries do n't have to buy the book <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said he receives up to 50 unsolicited nominations for new entrants each week _ either from admirers or the would-be personalities themselves. The publication has been in business since 1899. New editions are published every two years. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquis </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> publisher, founded the publication after seeing a similar book in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The idea was not to confer celebrity status on certain people, but to provide a useful reference book to businesses and libraries. The book does have a history of keeping a Who or two out. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was refused a listing for years because <PERSON> Marquis </PERSON> objected to the architect's unsettled married life. <PERSON> Marquis </PERSON> also barred 1930s Hollywood star Mae West from the big red book. That prompted her to respond, `` Well, the old boy who publishes that is n't in my little black book, either.''
