<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> helicopter carrying 16 soldiers and a crew of three crashed into a remote mountainside south of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> today, but only minor injuries were reported, officials said. The CH-47D Chinook transport helicopter was on a training mission when it crashed near <LOCATION> Osan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, 40 miles south of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, at about 10:30 a.m., said <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Sgt. <PERSON> Wilt </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> 8th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> public affairs office. The injured were treated at nearby hospitals, he said. Their names were withheld. The helicopter was assigned to B Company, 2nd Battalion, 501st Aviation Regiment stationed at Camp Humphreys south of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. American military officials said they were investigating the cause of the crash. The Army grounded most of its CH-47D Chinook helicopters in October because of a problem with transmission oil cooling fans. The fleet was grounded in August as a precaution while previous fan failures were studied. The helicopters were made by <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Helicopter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>.
