<HEAD>Clash Leaves One Dead, Parliament Member and Eight Constables Hurt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A black man was killed and at least 13 people, including eight policemen and a <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> member, were hurt when officers clashed with hundreds of blacks trying to attend a protest meeting, police said today. Constables were pelted with stones and responded by using stun grenades, rubber bullets and tear gas, policesaid. The clash occurred Sunday in <LOCATION> Edendale </LOCATION>, near the <ORGANIZATION> Natal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION> capital of <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION>, after more than 2,000 blacks gathered to attend an anti-government meeting. Authorities had refused to allow the meeting to be held at a stadium, and it was moved to a meeting hall that could accommodate only about 1,000 people. Police said those who could not fit inside became disorderly and began stoning officers and their vehicles. The police report did not specify how the death occurred. One of those injured was <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronje </PERSON>, a white <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> member for the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He was hit in the chest by a rock but not seriously hurt. Five other deaths were reported in political violence and faction fighting elsewhere in <LOCATION> Natal </LOCATION> in the 24 hours ending at daybreak today. More than 2,000 blacks have been killed in the province in the past three years in a power truggle between members of <ORGANIZATION> Inkatha </ORGANIZATION>, a relatively conservative Zulu organization, and supporters of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, a nationwide anti-apartheid coalition. The meeting in <LOCATION> Edendale </LOCATION> was organized by supporters of the front.
