<FIRST>u w PM-HomeSales     12-04 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Home Sales,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Home Sales Down Again, But Show Improvement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of new homes edged down 0.5 percent in October, the sixth monthly decline of the year but a major improvement over the previous month, the government reported today. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said new single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 649,000 units in October, after a 10.2 percent plunge in September. The September decrease was revised downward from a 14 percent fall originally reported last month. Fixed-rate mortgage interest rates fell to 9.82 percent by the end of October after rising into the double digits in September. Analysts had said the lower rates would lead to an improvement in the housing industry. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> reported last week that sales of existing homes remained steady in October at their highest level since last January and <ORGANIZATION> NAR </ORGANIZATION> chief economist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuccillo </PERSON> said then that `` home financing conditions probably will stay quite favorable in the months ahead.'' The housing industry was among the hardest hit when the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> pumped up interest rates last year to slow the economy and thus contain inflation. But as inflationary pressures cooled, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has permitted gradual decreases in rates since the beginning of the summer. The Realtors association reported today that its index measuring the ability of the typical American family to buy an existing home rose in October to its highest level in eight months because of stable rates and a drop in the median home price. The real estate group said the index rose to 106.1, from 103.5 in September and the highest since it measured 106.7 last February. That means a family with a median income of $ 33,365 had 106.1 percent of the income needed to buy a median-priced existing home costing $ 92,100. The median means that half of the families earn more and half less, or that half the homes sell for more and half for less. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report today said the median price of a new home was $ 127,900 in October, up 5.3 percent from $ 121,500 in September. The average price of a new home was unchanged at $ 151,900. New-home sales for the first nine months were down 4.4 percent from the same period in 1988. Sales rose 47.8 percent in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> but fell 24.7 percent in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. The South posted a 5.7 percent increase, while the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> recorded a 3.7 percent gain. The Realtors, meanwhile, said a family in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> earning the median income of $ 37,329 had only 76.1 percent of the income needed to buy median-priced existing home costing $ 143,300. In the West, a family earning the median income of $ 35,299 had 74.1 percent of the income needed to buy a home priced at $ 142,200. In the South, a family earning the median income of $ 30,533 had 107.4 percent of the income needed to buy an $ 83,400 home, while a Midwestern family earning the median of $ 33,511 had 137.5 percent of the income needed to purchase a home priced at $ 70,900.
</TEXT>
