<HEAD>Court Leaves Intact Ruling on Hazardous Waste Shipments in Alabama
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today left intact a ruling that limits the power of states and their citizens to block shipments of hazardous waste from other states. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> officials who failed to prevent shipments of hazardous waste from an abandoned <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> chemical refinery to <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> officials said they were denied a fair opportunity to oppose the shipments. The plans for removing the waste to <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> were approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> under the so-called Superfund law of 1980, aimed at helping clean up toxic waste. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> included an abandoned <ORGANIZATION> Geneva </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> petrochemical plant in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> among priority sites to be cleaned up. The site is contaminated with polychlorinated biphenyls -LRB- PCBs -RRB- and other toxic chemicals. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials in 1986, in cooperation with <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> officials, approved removal of the waste to another location. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> officials signed a contract with <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Waste </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- CWM -RRB- to have 47,000 tons of the waste shipped to the company's treatment facility in <LOCATION> Emelle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> officials, led by Gov <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, said they unlawfully were denied a chance to participate in the process that led to the selection of the <LOCATION> Emelle </LOCATION> facility. A federal judge temporarily blocked the shipment of the waste. But the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> overruled the judge in April and permitted the waste to be deposited at the <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> site. The appeals court noted that the <LOCATION> Emelle </LOCATION> facility is licensed by <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and the federal government to handle such toxic wastes. The appeals court added that federal laws controlling disposal of toxic substances `` ensure that <ORGANIZATION> CWM </ORGANIZATION>'s toxic waste storage and treatment facility poses the least possible risk to human health and safety.'' The appeals court also rejected arguments that the Constitution and federal laws guarantee <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> citizens and officials the opportunity to express opposition to such shipments before they take place. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration supported the appeals court ruling. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers noted that the Superfund law was amended in 1986 to bar challenges to clean-up decisions until after the clean-up is completed. The law `` does not preclude'' challenges such as the one made by the <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> officials, the government said. It only delays them `` until after remedial action has been taken and thus -LRB- the law -RRB- is clearly constitutional.'' The case is <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Enviromental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, 89-378.
