<HEAD>Court Agrees to Hear California Water Supply Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to hear arguments favoring states' rights and consider limiting the federal government's power to control water used by hydroelectric dams. The court said it will hear a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> appeal supported by more than 40 states. The water-rights dispute pits the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> against <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration sided with the federal commission, and environmentalists supported the state agency. The commission in 1983 licensed construction of a hydroelectric power project on <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, a small tributary of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Placerville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The dam's owner, <ORGANIZATION> Rock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partnership </ORGANIZATION>, plans to generate electric power and sell it to <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The state water resources agency sought to limit the flow of water over the dam by requiring that enough water continue flowing in <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> to assure survival of trout. But the federal commission in 1987 said it has exclusive control over how much water should flow over the dam. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled in favor of commission last June, saying the Federal Power Act `` strongly suggests that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> intended to vest final authority for the regulation of hyrdroelectric power projects in federal hands.'' The appeals court said that interpretation of the law is supported by a 1946 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling, which it said gave states control over water distribution only for limited purposes _ for irrigation and city water supplies. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> intended federal law to pre-empt state regulation in all aspects of hydropower projects save for the limited proprietary exceptions specified'' in the law, the appeals court said. Permitting the state to limit water supplied to the dam `` could jeopardize the economic feasibility of the project'' and undermine the federal licensing authority, the 9th Circuit court added. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s appeal was supported by a friend-of-the-court legal brief signed by the attorneys general of 43 other states. The only states not signing were <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. The 43 states said the appeals court ruling, if adopted nationwide, would `` fundamentally alter state control of water resources and eviscerate comprehensive state regulatory systems for allocating water.'' Leading environmental groups, including the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, said `` ill-conceived hyrdroelectric development'' should not be shielded from state regulation. But administration lawyers urged the justices to reject any call for what they said would be unworkable dual control over hydroelectric projects. The case is <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> FERC </ORGANIZATION>, 89-333.
