<HEAD>Court Sets Stage for Significant Ruling on Power to Fine Air Polluters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 4-11, In other action, with other cases.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today set the stage for a significant ruling on the government's power to fine air polluters. The court agreed to hear an appeal by <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, which faces fines of up to $ 25,000 a day for violating federal air quality standards at a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> car-assembly plant. The justices will review a ruling that the federal government's failure to meet a deadline for approving or rejecting revised state pollution controls does not bar it from fining <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> In other action, the court: _ Agreed to hear arguments favoring states' rights and consider limiting the federal government's power to control water used by hydroelectric dams. The court said it will hear a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> appeal supported by nearly every other state. _ Left intact a ruling that limits the power of states and their citizens to block shipments of hazardous waste from other states. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> officials who failed to prevent shipments of hazardous waste from an abandoned <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> chemical refinery to <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. _ Agreed to decide whether <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks with branch offices overseas must pay depositors after foreign governments seize or freeze those accounts. The court said it will review rulings that required <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> to pay depositors. Lawyers for <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> said billions of dollars are at stake. There are more than 900 branches of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks operating in 73 countries, with some $ 225 billion in deposits. _ Rejected a plea from <LOCATION> DeKalb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, school officials ordered to consider racial desegregation measures that include busing. The court refused to block a ruling that the county's school officials take further steps to integrate the 73,000-student school system, the largest in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. The air pollution case involves pollution from car paint at <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s plant in <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>, and focuses on the joint federal-state system for cleaning up the atmosphere Under the federal Clean Air Act, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> sets national air quality standards. The states are required to adopt plans to meet those standards, and submit the plans to the EPA. The federal agency in 1980 approved a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> plan for reducing pollution from paint at auto assembly factories. The plan required car makers to comply fully with the federal rules by Dec. 31, 1985. But <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials extended the deadline for any plant switching from lacquer paints to enamel, which emits less pollutants. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> initially planned to stay with lacquer at the <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION> factory but in June 1985 announced it would convert to enamel by the summer of 1987. The company asked that it not be required to comply with the Dec. 31, 1985, standards until 20 months later. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> officials approved <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s proposal and submitted a revised plan to the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> on Dec. 30, 1985. Without waiting for federal approval, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> began building a $ 200 million plant in <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION> to use the enamel system while continuing to operate its factory that uses lacquer paint. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials went to federal court in August 1987 seeking fines of up to $ 25,000 a day against <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> for 20 months of air-quality violations at the old <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION> plant. It was not until September 1988 that the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> rejected the state-approved pollution control system at the new plant. A federal judge barred the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> from imposing fines against <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> for violations of the Dec. 31, 1985, standards. The judge said the federal agency itself violated the Clean Air Act by taking more than four months to rule on the state-approved plan submitted Dec. 30, 1985. But the 1st U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last June said the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s failure to meet the four-month deadline does not disqualify it from fining companies that violate previously approved pollution control rules. The public should not be penalized with dirtier air because of what often are unavoidable EPA delays, the appeals court said. It told the trial judge to decide how much the fines should be, stating he should take into account whether the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s delay was reasonable and what impact the delay had on <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> joined <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> in urging the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to review the air pollution dispute. <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> lawyers said the 1st Circuit court ruling is an incentive to the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to treat companies unfairly. They said it conflicts with decisions by other federal appeals courts. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration said the 1st Circuit court's ruling was correct. The case is <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 89-369.
