<HEAD>Catastrophic-Coverage Payments Will Continue Well Into New Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retirees will have to continue paying monthly premiums for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> catastrophic coverage at least until May, even though the program is being repealed this month, federal officials said today. That much time will be required to adjust and test the government computers that now withhold the premiums from monthly Social Security benefit checks, Social Security Commissioner <PERSON> Gwendolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> said in an interview today. She said the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> hopes to stop deducting the premiums starting with the benefit checks that arrive in early May. Refunds of the premiums could take three or more months beyond that date. The $ 4-a-month premium for catastrophic coverage is scheduled under the law to rise to $ 5.30 on Jan. 1. Although <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> voted last month to repeal catastrophic protection, the bill has not yet been presented to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for his signature. `` My concern is for those on fixed income who can not afford to see $ 5 go out of their checks,'' Ms. <PERSON> King </PERSON> said. `` That's a lot of money for those people and it is little consolation for them to know they will get a refund in the future.'' The prospect of seeing retirees continue to have to pay the premiums does not sit well either with Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, D-Ark., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aging </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` I fear that a lengthy delay will create a firestorm of protest,'' <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> said in a letter to Ms. <PERSON> King </PERSON> that was made public today. `` We must recognize the impending firestorm and move repidly to alleviate the problem.'' <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> said many retirees will need the $ 5.30 a month to pay the expected increase in rates for private `` Medigap'' policies as a result of repeal of federal coverage. Catastrophic coverage was enacted last year to protect people 65 and older from being bankrupted by a major illness. The program fell into disfavor with many retirees, especially those who already have private coverage and higher-income people who were faced with an income surtax of up to $ 800 a year for catastrophic. As a result of loud complaints from those groups, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> agreed last month to kill the program. The monthly premiums that have been deducted from benefit checks this year will not be refunded; they will pay for hospital and other benefits that have been in effect all year. Few retirees have been paying the surtax. Those who have paid it through quarterly estimated tax payments will get a larger-than-expected income tax refund next year.
</TEXT>
