<HEAD>EPA Calls for Curbs on EBDC Family of Pesticides</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 grafs with crops affected by withdrawal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assoicated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> today called for sharp curbs on the widely used EBDC family of pesticides, proposing that the chemical no longer be applied to 42 crops including apples and tomatoes because of concerns about cancer. The proposed regulation, which would not become final until early 1991, would allow the continued use of the EBDC fungicides on 10 crops including grapes, onion and cranberries. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said the use of the <ORGANIZATION> EBDCs </ORGANIZATION> _ known as maneb, mancozeb and metiram _ on the remaining 10 crops `` do not present an unreasonable risk.'' The agency estimated the maximum risk of someone getting cancer from a lifetime of exposure at three in 1 million. With the chemical's current widespread use that risk is 4 in 10,000, it said. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> applauded a decision announced earlier this year by EBDC manufacturers to withdraw the chemical's use on 42 crops But he said `` we do not believe that goes far enough'' and proposed that the ban apply as well to three additional crops _ tomatoes, bananas and potatoes. The manufacturers have said they would begin their voluntary curbs at the end of the year. EBDC use on the other three crops would not go into effect for at least 18 months unless producers choose to incorporate them in their voluntary curb. The EBDC chemicals, which began to be used in the 1930s, are among the most widely used fungicides, with as much as 18 million pounds manufactured annually for use on most common vegetables as well as grains. But the fungicide has come under attack from environmentalists and health specialists because a breakdown product called ETU has been found to cause cancer in laboratory animals. Chronic exposure also raises the risks of birth defects or thyroid disorders, scientists said. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said that while the health risks associated with <ORGANIZATION> EBDC </ORGANIZATION> use on any one crop may be negligible, `` the cumulative risks -LRB- associated with its widespread use -RRB- has been determined to be unreasonable.'' The health risk estimates are based on the maximum allowable dosage of the fungicide on various crops. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said those estimates likely are greater than residue levels found in the marketplace because the fungicide is easily washed off. Crop producers as well as state agriculture departments had asked the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to hold off proposing restrictions on the <ORGANIZATION> EBDCs </ORGANIZATION> until a marketbasket survey currently under way is completed to provide a clearer picture of residue levels actually found on crops by consumers. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Departments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> said in a letter to <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> that several states already had reported results of surveys and `` to date no significant residues of <ORGANIZATION> EBDCs </ORGANIZATION> have been found.'' Environmental groups, however, have criticized the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> for moving too slowely in getting the <ORGANIZATION> EBDCs </ORGANIZATION> off the market, noting that a final regulation on the chemical will not be issued until the spring of 1991. Under the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> proposal, <ORGANIZATION> EBDCs </ORGANIZATION> would continue to be used on grapes, wheat, cranberries, onions, sugar beets, sweet corn, peanuts, almonds, asparagus and figs. The 42 crops on which EBDCs currently are used, but would no longer be used under voluntary curbs by the chemical's manufacturers, are: Apples, apricots, barley, casaba melons, crenshaw melons, cucumbers, eggplants, endives, lettuce, pineapples, pumpkins, green beans, dried beans, <LOCATION> lima </LOCATION> beans, broccoli, <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> sprouts, cabbage, cantaloupes, carrots, cauliflower, celery, collards, field corn, cotton, crabapples, fennel, honeydew melons, kale, kohlrabi, mustard greens, nectarines, oats, papayas, peaches, pears, pecans, peppers, rhubarb, rye, squash, spinach, turnips and watermelon
