<HEAD>Woman Receives World's First Heart-Liver-Kidney Transplant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with doctors' news conference
today, family background, anti-rejection drug, husband's comments. Picks
up 8th graf pvs, ``Her operation....''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CASSANDRA BURRELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 26-year-old woman has a new heart, liver, and kidney after an almost daylong operation that doctors called the first of its kind. <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Archbald </LOCATION> remained in critical condition today at <LOCATION> Presbyterian-University </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, which is normal after transplant surgery. At a news conference this morning, doctors said they would try to begin weaning her off a respirator today. Other multiorgan transplants have been performed, but this was the first involving the heart, liver and a kidney, said transplant pioneer Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Starzl </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION>'s transplant program. The procedure began at 7:35 p.m. Saturday and ended at 5 p.m. Sunday. It was Ms. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>'s second heart transplant. She has familial cardiomyopathy, an inherited heart disease, according to the hospital. Mrs. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>'s family has a history of congenital heart problems. Her father died when he was 31 and many relatives on his side of the family also have died young, her husband, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, 28, said today. Mrs. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> suffered from chronic rejection of the heart she received in her first transplant three years ago, and had developed hepatitis and kidney dysfunction. Kidney dysfunction can affect patients taking the anti-rejection drug cyclosporine. Doctors will treat Mrs. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> with the Japanese drug FK-506, which is believed 50 to 100 times more effective than cyclosporine, hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Rossi </PERSON> said. FK-506 has been tested since February in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> on liver, heart, kidney, pancreas and lung recipients. The new organs came from an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> woman in her 20s who was killed in a car accident, doctors said. When doctors called Saturday to say a donor had been found, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said he had to scramble to locate his wife. `` We had a tough time finding her at first because she was out shopping when the call came,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. `` I'm nervous of course. The first transplant sort of prepared me a little for this, but I'm just nervous as to what the outcome might be.'' Her operation came five days after another milestone in transplant operations. In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, 21-month-old <PERSON> Alyssa </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> became the nation's first person to receive part of a liver from a living donor. <PERSON> Alyssa </PERSON> was listed in serious condition Sunday, and is improving steadily, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Easton </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Wyler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Alyssa </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON>, was the donor. The world's first survivor of a heart-liver transplant was <PERSON> Stormie </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, now 12, of White Settlement, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Starzl </PERSON> conducted that procedure on Feb. 14, 1984, at Children's Hospital of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. Two other heart-liver transplants were performed the next year in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, but both patients died with a few days of surgery. <PERSON> Starzl </PERSON> also has headed multiple-organ transplant operations involving the intestines. <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>, 3, of <LOCATION> Madisonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, survived six months before dying in May 1988 after a multiple-organ transplant. <LOCATION> Rolandrea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dodge </LOCATION>, 3, of <LOCATION> Fruitland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, died last January, six weeks after surgery. <PERSON> Starzl </PERSON> also has headed multiple-organ transplants on adults with malignant, inoperable tumors in the pancreas and liver areas. In those cases, surgeons have removed the patient's liver, pancreas, most or all of the stomach, two-thirds of the colon, and duodenum, a 10-inch-long section of the small intestine. The cavity has been filled with a block of organs consisting of the liver, pancreas, duodenum and jejunum, a few feet of section of the small intestine.
