<HEAD>Hospital Fire Leaves One Patient Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A hospital bed mattress was set afire by the cigarette of a patient smoking in bed, and the 77-year-old smoker was killed, officials said. Nurses at <LOCATION> Parkway </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> discovered the fire after a smoke alarm sounded early Sunday in the private room of <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurtz </PERSON>, who was recovering from prostrate surgery, said chief marketing officer <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>. A nurse pulled <PERSON> Kurtz </PERSON> onto the floor while another staff member fought the blaze, which was confined to <PERSON> Kurtz </PERSON>'s room. About 40 other patients on the wing were evacuated while the fire was being fought. <PERSON> Kurtz </PERSON> suffered third-degree and fourth-degree burns over 80 percent of his body. He was taken to <PERSON> Hermann </PERSON> <PERSON> Hospital </PERSON>, where he died about two hours later. The incident will be reviewed to see if policy changes should be made regarding smokers, <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> said.
