<HEAD>Former Prison Hostage Sues to Get Videotapes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former guard who has had emotional problems since he was held hostage during a 1987 riot at the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> federal prison is suing to get government videotapes his psychologist says can help him end his ordeal. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Mormann </PERSON>, 36, was one of about 100 hostages held by Cuban detainees during the 11-day takeover at the penitentiary two years ago. A number of people held hostage at the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> prison and during a related prison confrontation at <LOCATION> Oakdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, have reported serious emotional problems. Soon after his release, <PERSON> Mormann </PERSON> accepted a transfer to a prison in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, where the mostly Hispanic prison population reminded him of the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> prison. `` I flipped out,'' he said, adding that he suffered a panic attack that put him in a psychiatric ward for a month. His wife and daughter left him, and he has since divorced. He returned to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> in July 1988 and lives on worker's compensation. The federal <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisons </ORGANIZATION> confirms that tapes of the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> riot exist, but has told <ORGANIZATION> Mormann </ORGANIZATION> he was not specific enough as to which ones he wished to see when he tried to get copies through the Freedom of Information Act. He sued in federal court when that effort failed. `` How can we be more specific? We do n't even know what's on the tapes,'' said psychologist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Aycock </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jonesboro </LOCATION>, who has been treating Mormann for a year. `` It's not like there's a national security risk here. ... We're just looking for anything that can bring him back into the situation.'' <PERSON> Aycock </PERSON> said the tapes could help <PERSON> Mormann </PERSON> realize what he went through and help him get on with his life. `` He can watch the tapes and be anxious, cut it off and go back to it when he calms down. Control is the key,'' <PERSON> Aycock </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Aycock </PERSON> said <PERSON> Mormann </PERSON> has post-traumatic stress disorder, similar to that of some war or disaster survivors, and suffers nightmares and flashbacks. On the day of the Nov. 23, 1987, takeover, <PERSON> Aycock </PERSON> was the only guard in a dormitory of about 70 Cubans considered to be model prisoners. He locked himself in an office, but the inmates broke the door down with a desk. He was handcuffed, tied and forced at knifepoint to be a human shield for the transfer of two wounded prisoners. He was kept handcuffed to another guard in a cell for the duration of the takeover. The Cubans detained at the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> prison were among those who came to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the Mariel boatlift of 1980. Thousands who had criminal records or got into trouble after arrival were held pending deportation. Since the riot, 122 have been sent back to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, 789 remain in custody and 3,250 have been released to halfway houses, relatives or other sponsors.
