<HEAD>Thatcher Faces First Leadership Challenge in 14 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> faces re-election as <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader Tuesday, and for the first time since she got the job 14 years ago, she has a challenger. Sir <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, a rank-and-file legislator little known outside <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, does n't expect to win. But he hopes to get enough votes to send Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> a message of discontent at a time of 7.3 percent inflation and difficulties over <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s place in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Younger </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s campaign manager, said Monday that out of the 374 Conservative members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> eligible to cast ballots, he expected up to 20 will vote for <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> Some are expected to abstain in a show of disapproval of Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s sometimes autocratic leadership style, and her reluctance to accept some of the new rules dictated by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s membership in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tory </ORGANIZATION> lawmaker <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> says estimates of anti-Thatcher votes and abstentions range from 23 to 66, with an average prediction of 45. Forty-five would do Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> little harm. Analysts agree it would take 100 or more to wound her, and no one expects her to lose outright. Early guesses are tricky, because many members have refused to state their preference before they put their votes in the ballot box. The waverers face a dilemma: they want to send her a message, but not such an overwhelming one that she will feel obliged to resign. Conservative lawmakers vote annually on their leader, and Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, 64, has been endorsed without opposition since 1975 when she ousted former Prime Minister <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Heath </PERSON>. She has led the Conservative to three successive election victories since 1979, become the longest-serving <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> prime minister this century, and said she wants to go on and on. But public opinion polls show she is the least popular prime minister this century, her <ORGANIZATION> Tories </ORGANIZATION> are up to 15 points behind the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, and her sweeping economic and social reforms have gone too far for many voters. `` While the rich have become richer in the past 10 years, the poor have become poorer,'' said <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, a 69-year-old former diplomat who represents a Welsh constituency and has always been on the liberal anti-Thatcher wing of the party. `` There is a real limit on the extent to which the electorate is prepared to tolerate public squalor, whether in filthy streets, worsening public transport or inadequate schools or hospitals in return for private affluence,'' he said Monday. Younger said in a weekend television interview that <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> wrongly believes `` there is a vast groundswell who want him to do this. I'm afraid the truth is there is n't and people mostly would very much wish he had n't.'' To be reelected on the first ballot, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> needs 57 percent of the 374 eligible votes _ a majority plus 15 percent. If she fails, up to two more ballots can be held until a winner emerges on a simply majority of 188 votes. The victor becomes party leader and prime minister, subject only to the formality of royal approval. The Conservatives hold 375 of the 650 seats in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION>, but Speaker <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Weatherill </PERSON> does not vote. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, who has a vote, said last week the leadership vote was bad for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and for the party, but she defended <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>'s democratic right to challenge her. Opinion polls consistently have named another former <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> secretary, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Heseltine </PERSON>, as the person voters would most like to replace Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>. <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> has said he mounted the challenge not in any hope of winning, but as a way of enticing more likely candidates into the race. However <PERSON> Heseltine </PERSON> has repeatedly said he wo n't participate in the campaign to unseat Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, although he has not indicated whether he will cast a ballot or abstain Tuesday.
