<HEAD>Court Will Study Government's Power to Fine Polluters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it will decide whether the federal government's delays in setting clean-air guidelines limit its power to fine polluters. The justices said they will hear an appeal by <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, which faces fines of up to $ 25,000 a day for violating air-quality standards at a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> car-assembly plant. A lower court rejected <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s claims that it should be shielded from fines because of federal delays on proposed revisions in state pollution controls. The public should not be penalized with dirtier air because of what often are unavoidable delays by the federal <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, the 1st U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled. In other action, the court: _ Agreed to consider limiting the federal government's power to control water used by hydroelectric dams The court said it will hear a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> appeal supported by more than 40 states. _ Refused to enhance the power of states and their citizens to block shipments of hazardous waste from other states The court rejected an appeal by <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> officials who failed to prevent shipments of hazardous waste from an abandoned <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> chemical refinery. _ Agreed to decide whether <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks with branch offices overseas must pay depositors after foreign governments seize or freeze those accounts The court will review a ruling that required <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> to pay depositors. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> nomination was defeated by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1987, is representing <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>. _ Left intact a victory for rock star Prince by refusing to revive a copyright-infringement claim by his half-sister over the hit song `` U Got The Look. The air-pollution case involves a <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> plant in <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, and focuses on the joint federal-state system for cleaning up the atmosphere. Under the federal Clean Air Act, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> sets national air quality standards and states must adopt plans to meet those standards. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> in 1980 approved a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> plan for reducing pollution from paint at auto-assembly factories. The plan required car makers to comply fully with the federal rules by Dec. 31, 1985. But <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials extended the deadline for any plant switching from lacquer to enamel paints, which emit less pollutants. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> initially planned to stay with lacquer at the <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION> factory but in June 1985 announced it would convert to enamel paint by the summer of 1987. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> asked that it not be required to comply with the Dec. 31, 1985, standards until 20 months later. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> officials approved <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s proposal and submitted a revised plan to the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> on Dec. 30, 1985. Without waiting for federal approval, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> began building a $ 200 million plant in <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION> to use enamel-based paints while continuing to operate its existing factory. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials went to federal court in August 1987 seeking fines of up to $ 25,000 a day against <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> for 20 months of air-quality violations at the old plant. But it was not until September 1988 that the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> rejected the state-approved pollution-control system at the new plant. A federal judge barred the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> from fining <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> for violations of the Dec. 31, 1985, standards, ruling that the federal agency itself violated the Clean Air Act by taking more than four months to rule on the state-approved plan submitted Dec. 30, 1985. But the 1st Circuit court last June said the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s failure to meet the four-month deadline does not disqualify it from fining companies that violate previously approved pollution-control rules. The appeals court told the trial judge to decide how much the fines should be, advising him to consider whether the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s delay was reasonable and what impact the delay had on <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> joined <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> in urging the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to review the dispute. <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> lawyers said the 1st Circuit court ruling invites unfair treatment for businesses. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration said the 1st Circuit court ruling was correct.
