<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the four other <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact nations that invaded <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> in 1968 to crush a reform movement today condemned the action. The statement came as East bloc leaders, including the first non-communist head of state, met for a <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> meeting to hear President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s report on his recent talks with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The leaders of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> said the entrance of their troops into <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> 21 years ago constitituted `` interference in the internal affairs of a sovereign <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and must be condemned.'' `` Interrupting the process of democratic renewal in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, these unjustified actions had long-term negative consequences,'' added the statement, which was read on the evening news and carried by the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency. The Soviet-led invasion crushed the `` Prague Spring'' reforms of <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, who was subsequently ousted as the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader. He has since re-emerged as one of the spokespeople of the pro-democracy movement sweeping <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> briefing <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> leaders on the summit. Dutch Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> den </PERSON> <PERSON> Broek </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </P