<HEAD>New-Home Sales Off But Analysts Predict Some Improvement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of new homes fell 0.5 percent in October, the government reported Monday. Analysts said overall purchases were driven down by a 24.7 percent decline in the West due to the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay-area </LOCATION> earthquake and the effects of the slowing economy. But economists said the sales pace should improve somewhat over the next few months as mortgage interest rates drop to the mid-9 percent range. No analyst predicted a surge in sales. `` The report says that housing market activity has improved some from the sluggish pace of March and February, but that the market is by no means taking off,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Holloway </PERSON>, senior economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said new single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 649,000 in October following a revised 10.2 percent plunge in September. September sales originally were reported down 14 percent. Sales in the West fell 53,000 units on an annual basis to 161,000 homes. But all other regions posted gains, prompting <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Berson </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, to conclude `` the earthquake appeared to keep people from buying new homes.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Carliner </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Builders </ORGANIZATION>, said economic sluggishness also contributed to the lack of western sales. Part of the problem, he said, was slower defense spending, which resulted in significant layoffs. Home sales had fallen dramatically earlier this year as the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> pumped up interest rates to slow the economy and thus contain inflation. As inflationary pressures cooled, however, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has permitted gradual decreases in rates since the beginning of the summer. Fixed-rate mortgage interest rates fell to an average of 9.82 percent by the end of October after rising into the double digits in September, according to a survey by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Despite the lower interest rates, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Niemira </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said `` the new home market appears to be hurt by the ever-widening gap between new and existing home prices. `` Builders also appear to be misreading the current market,'' he said. `` It is a market for low-priced homes and builders generally are not building for that market.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the median price of a new home in October rose 5.3 percent to $ 127,900. The median means half of the homes cost more and half less. The average price of a new home was unchanged at $ 151,900. On the other hand, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday that the median price of an existing single-family home was $ 92,100. New home sales in the Northeast rose 47.8 percent but <ORGANIZATION> Fannie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Berson </PERSON> said that reflected a low September sales count rather than growing market strength in the area. The South posted a 5.7 percent increase, while the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> recorded a 3.7 percent gain. New-home sales for the first nine months were down 4.4 percent from the same period in 1988. In its report, the real estate trade group said that its index measuring the ability of the typical American family to buy an existing home rose in October to its highest level in eight months because of stable mortgage rates and a drop in the median home price. The real estate group said the index rose to 106.1, from 103.5 in September and was the highest since it was 106.7 last February. That means a family with a median income of $ 33,365 had 106.1 percent of the income needed to buy a median-priced existing home costing $ 92,100.
