<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government's broadcast service, opened its second Soviet bloc bureau Monday and launched discussions with Polish state radio on the exchange of programming. `` They were jamming us two years ago,'' said <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>. To mark the opening of the <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> bureau, <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> prepared a live Monday night program permitting callers in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to discuss their country's economic situation with Polish-speaking experts in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>. `` This is unheard of given the context of our journalistic relationship with this country so recently,'' <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> said. `` It is definitely amazing. We did not envision this at all.'' <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION>, which broadcasts in 43 languages to an estimated 130 million people worldwide, for years was jammed by East bloc countries and denounced by their leaders. <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> correspondents were denied visas to work in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> or given only limited access. Jamming has ended in the Soviet bloc in recent years, <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> said, and <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> opened a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> bureau last year. <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION>, heard by an estimated 50 percent of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s adults at least once a week, was given permanent accreditation in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in April, <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> said. No full-time correspondent has been assigned due to budget constraints, but the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> bureau will be staffed on a rotating basis by reporters stationed elsewhere. A <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> bureau also is being established by <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION>, another long-time propaganda enemy for its uncensored reports to <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The strict state control of Polish radio and TV loosened in 1988. The Solidarity-led government of <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>, who became the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc's first non-communist leader in August, has vowed to free the flow of information. On Nov. 13, Polish Radio ran a live broadcast, provided by the <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION>, of Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s speech to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION>, which produces six hours of live Polish-language reports daily from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> headquarters, will continue talks with Polish authorities on placing its programming on state radio, <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> said. Also being discussed are exchanges of broadcasters and training programs, <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> correspondents are being welcomed elsewhere in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> as well. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> offers virtually free access, and <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> has provided ongoing accreditaion for Czech and English-language correspondents, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> recently allowed a <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> rep