<HEAD>Catastrophiiic Payments Continuing Beyond Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly 33 million retirees will have to pay premiums for several more months for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> catastrophic coverage _ a program that will be abolished on Dec. 31. <PERSON> Gwendolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, commissioner of the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, blamed <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' late action in repealing the law. She said Monday there is no way that Social Security computers can be adjusted more quickly to halt withholding of the premiums from monthly benefit checks. The premiums will be refunded in a lump sum later, Ms. <PERSON> King </PERSON> said. `` We have people going flat out ... but we wo n't be able to make all the changes until perhaps the end of April or the beginning of May,'' Ms. <PERSON> King </PERSON> said. That means the great majority of retirees _ perhaps up to 29 million _ will have to pay $ 5.30 a month for three or four months for a program that will no longer exist. Some retirees pay less; others pay more. `` The bottom line is that Social Security will unscramble this egg, but we did not lay it,'' Ms. <PERSON> King </PERSON> said. Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, D-Ark., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aging </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said in a letter to Ms. <PERSON> King </PERSON> that `` a lengthy delay -LRB- in halting collection of the premiums -RRB- will create a firestorm of protest We must recognize the impending firestorm and move rapidly to alleviate the problem.'' <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> predicted that if the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> continues withholding the premiums until early summer, it could take the rest of the year for retirees to get their money back. <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> estimated that would temporarily take $ 1 billion out of the pockets of the elderly. In many cases, he said, they need that money to pay private `` Medigap'' insurance policy premium increases expected to result from repeal of federal catastrophic coverage. `` We knew there might be a problem but I do n't think we expected it to take this long to resolve,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rother </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Persons </ORGANIZATION>. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> normally gives the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administraton </ORGANIZATION> about a three-month lead time for changes.'' Since Jan. 1, most people 65 and older have been paying $ 4 a month to finance part of the cost of Medicare catastrophic coverage. The year-old program aims to prevent a retiree from being by bankrupted by a major illness. The monthly premium is scheduled to rise to $ 5.30 on Jan. 1. Premiums paid this year will not be refunded; they finance extended hospital coverage and other, minor catastrophic benefits that have been in effect since January. Two-thirds of the cost of the program would have been borne by higher-income retirees through an income surtax of up to $ 800 a year. Officials have no way of knowing whether those people have been making periodic payments of the surtax along with their quarterly estimated payments of income tax. Those who have, and those past 65 who are earning wages and may have paid the surtax through the withholding system, will be able to subtract the surtax from taxes due with they file their returns early next year. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> repealed catastrophic because of protests from those higher-income retirees and from others who have a private catastrophic plan or coverage geared to their retirement benefits. The repeal vote came Nov. 22. Although <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has adjourned until Jan. 23, the bill has not yet been delivered to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for his signature. That could come this week. Ms. <PERSON> King </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rother </PERSON> said they regret that some people with the lowest income will be hurt by the delay in halting collection of the premiums. `` My concern is for those on fixed income who can not afford to see $ 5 go out of their checks,'' Ms. <PERSON> King </PERSON> said. `` That's a lot of money for those people and it is little consolation for them to know they will get a refund in the future.''
