<DATELINE>FARMINGTON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Love has found new champions in the battle to allow a Finnish exchange student to return to high school here after being banished to <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> because he was spending too much time with his American girlfriend. <PERSON> Iiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehtinen </PERSON>, 18, said he was given two hours to pack his bags Nov. 11 before being transferred to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, because exchange program leaders said his friendship with <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> <PERSON> LaPointe </PERSON> was causing his grades to suffer. <PERSON> Lehtinen </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Farmington </LOCATION> briefly Sunday, spent about an hour at <ORGANIZATION> LaPointe </ORGANIZATION>'s home with her and her family, met with a state legislator who has taken an interest in the case and was interviewed for two national television programs. His transfer prompted a walk-out last week of about 100 students, a third of <PERSON> Farmington </PERSON>'s student body. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Study </ORGANIZATION>, which sponsors the exchange program, say <PERSON> Lehtinen </PERSON> was transferred because he was spending too much time with <PERSON> LaPointe </PERSON> and not enough time with his host family. The group's regional director, <PERSON> Meg </PERSON> <PERSON> Holliday </PERSON>, has denied anyone from her organization told the youths they had to break up, but <PERSON> Lehtinen </PERSON> said he was told by an official after he got to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> that he had two weeks to break up with <PERSON> LaPointe </PERSON>. He said the order since has been replaced with directives limiting him to one visit and two telephone conversations with <ORGANIZATION> LaPointe </ORGANIZATION> a month. State Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsiros </PERSON> said the move was an insult to <PERSON> Farmington </PERSON>'s hospitality and a violation of the boy's civil rights. The foundation and the host family `` are missing the point that it is normal for an 18-year-old boy to have a romantic relationship with a girl,'' <PERSON> Tsiros </PERSON> said. <PERSON> LaPointe </PERSON>, 17, said the foundation officials make it sound like she sat around all day in front of the television waiting for <PERSON> Lehtinen </PERSON> to come over. `` I'm on the honor roll, I'm a Big Sister and I play sports year-round,'' she said. `` Whenever <PERSON> Iiro </PERSON> and I were together we were out with other people at high school games and functions.'' <PERSON> Tsiros </PERSON> said he has called state officials in <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION>, federal officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and the foundation headquarters in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> to try to bring <PERSON> Lehtinen </PERSON> back. And the boy's father has been lobbying from <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> to reverse the decision. The host family wo n't talk about the dispute.
