<HEAD>World War II Horror Revived in Britain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> is shedding the legacy of World War II, a British libel trial has in a way resurrected it. The case that Britons were reading about in their Sunday newspapers, even as President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> were meeting to shape the post-postwar era, revived a little-known horror in May 1945, when the British army repatriated 70,000 Cossack and Yugoslav refugees to a grisly fate at the hands of their communist enemies. The trial ended last week in a record $ 2.6 million award, and showed the abiding power of World War II to disrupt lives and pose painful questions a generation later. The victorious plaintiff in the High Court in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> was <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Aldington </PERSON>, former <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> deputy chairman, business leader and college head. In 1945 he was Brig. <PERSON> Toby </PERSON> <PERSON> Low </PERSON>, the officer based in Allied-occupied <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> who was ordered to implement the deportation. The most prominent defendant was Count <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolstoy </PERSON>, a historian who had written a pamphlet accusing <PERSON> Aldington </PERSON> of responsibility for sending the Cossacks and Yugoslavs, men, women and children, to the firing squads or labor camps. <PERSON> Aldington </PERSON>, 74, endured 30 hours of cross-examination. At one stage he stopped answering questions and wept. <PERSON> Tolstoy </PERSON> and co-defendant <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Watts </PERSON>, a realtor who distributed the pamphlet, were ordered to pay the damages plus an almost equal sum in legal costs. <PERSON> Tolstoy </PERSON> said the verdict had left him financially ruined. For some, the case had modern-day resonances in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s imminent plans to repatriate 40,000 Vietnamese boat people encamped in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> Columnist <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, 46, wrote in The Sunday Times that his generation should be wary of using hindsight to judge officers acting 44 years ago in the chaotic aftermath of a five-year war. But he wondered whether after the boat people were dealt with, `` after hundreds more deaths, will there be remorseful memoirs, bitter accusations _ and yet more libel trials?'' The Russian Cossacks and Yugoslavs who had fled the Soviet army to safety behind British lines were anti-Communist, anti-Soviet, and in many cases had fought for the Germans. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> had agreed secretly with Soviet dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> to return all Soviet and Yugoslav prisoners. It had no illusions the evacuees faced a rough time after repatriation, but felt bound by the agreement in order to ensure the repatriation of its own prisoners in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> hands. The story that unfolded over nine weeks in the packed court was filled with anguish. It told of British authorities resorting to subterfuge, telling the prisoners they were being sent to safety in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>; of prisoners killing themselves while still in British hands; of British soldiers allowing prisoners to escape rather than have them on their conscience; of other soldiers rifle-butting them into the trains, despising them for having been pro-German. <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicolson </PERSON>, a young officer at the time, remembered seeing men herded into cattle trucks and sent screaming to certain execution. `` We considered it one of the most disgraceful operations any British troops anywhere had been ordered to undertake,'' <PERSON> Nicolson </PERSON>, now 72, testified. <PERSON> Aldington </PERSON> said he had only obeyed orders and had no reason to believe executions would follow. `` There were many officers who were very unhappy about what we had to do and I was amongst them, but I did n't make a fuss about it. I just got on with my job,'' he testified. <PERSON> Aldington </PERSON> told his cross-examiner: `` You say I knew they were going to be massacred. That is not what I was told. I was told that war criminals would be tried and others would be put to work. `` It is terrible what happened, I know. Nobody's denying that what happened was ghastly. I do n't understand why you want to harry me over and over again.'' <PERSON> Tolstoy </PERSON>, the British-born grandson of a Russian Cossack, has written several books aimed at exposing what he calls an `` inexcusable cover-up in British public life.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Knight </PERSON>, a teacher of European studies who testified for <PERSON> Aldington </PERSON>, wrote in the Guardian that <PERSON> Tolstoy </PERSON> had `` sunk into the swamp of his own conspiracy theory.'' In summing up, the judge said some might think the verdict would settle the debate for good. `` It would be very nice to think it would,'' he said. `` But it seems to me unlikely that will happen.''
