<HEAD>Heady Revolution Pervades Every Corner of Prague</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A defiant liberty bell stands on a hill above <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, but many now notice revolutionaries failed to add a clapper to their makeshift symbol. They're still building the revolution. `` The Communists are playing for time, and we ca n't rest a minute,'' said <PERSON> Lenka </PERSON> <PERSON> Ressova </PERSON>, a young technician, before joining more than 150,000 people Monday on <LOCATION> Wenceslas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. The crowd, chanting, `` Resign! Resign!'' delivered its verdict on a new Communist-dominated Cabinet meant to shape a new <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. In thundering unison, people added, `` Free elections!'' But at opposition headquarters, Civic Forum leaders wrestled with a problem now familiar as the Iron Curtain tatters: Where to find popular, experienced leaders in societies ruled 40 years by a single ideology. `` They're fighting over every line,'' reported a Civic Forum member, emerging from strategy talks over how to protest a new government of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> holdovers and only five little-known outsiders. `` This will not be easy.'' He asked anonymity, no longer afraid of secret police but wanted to stay clear of internal politics. The overall mood is confident, even ebullient, as Czechoslovaks try out new freedoms few dreamed were possible only weeks ago. But cold, hard realism has replaced the first warm rush. A clear strain of anxiety that marked faces at Monday's mass rally was reflected all over town. Politics penetrated every crevice of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>. `` No one talks of anything else,'' said <PERSON> Hana </PERSON> <PERSON> Lingerova </PERSON>, slinging plates of roast pork at the Old Synagogue cafe. She amused customers by making folds in a banknote to turn a pictured Communist hero into the movie alien from `` E.T. _ The Extra-Terrestrial.'' In downtown metro stops, huge crowds mobbed public TV sets. In the outskirts, people rose at 3:30 a.m. to get the morning papers before they sold out. At the <ORGANIZATION> Charles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Faculty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physics </ORGANIZATION>, frazzled students watched TV, nibbled at stale sandwiches and churned out leaflets on their prehistoric computers. <PERSON> Milan </PERSON> <PERSON> Horak </PERSON>, 21, studied a visiting reporter's passport with more care than the immigration officer at <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. `` Infiltrators are trying to sneak in, to divide us and change our minds,'' he said. A revolutionary guard was comprised of four sleepy students armed with a guitar. <PERSON> Horak </PERSON> acknowledged that although people demand that the Communists hand over power, no alternate leaders were emerging. `` Our leaders are compromised, and the people who could lead were driven off,'' he said. Asked about <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, <PERSON> Horak </PERSON> gave the awkward shrug which often greets that name. <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, a powerful symbol, led <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> to the `` Prague Spring'' that was crushed by <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> tanks 21 years ago. But for most young people, he has been a Communist for too long. <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, the playwright whose life-long insistence on human freedoms shaped the script for the revolution, rejects any prolonged role in the politics of what comes next. In the vacuum of power, untested names rise in moments of glory. There are insistent calls for <PERSON> Valtr </PERSON> <PERSON> Komarek </PERSON>, a reform-minded economist, but critics say he is blemished by his close ties to the failing system. `` Now comes the hard part, the pressure of the mind,'' said <PERSON> Jaroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Nesetril </PERSON>, a professor who dropped in to check on the students. `` The Communists are more experienced, more organized. It is in nature that everything is reversible.'' In the bowels of the ABC Theater, people who helped bring off the revolution harbor few illusions about the next act. They admire <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> and the intellectuals around him, but most agree it is time for others to move in. `` That is the question, where to find the leaders,'' said <PERSON> Ivo </PERSON> <PERSON> Niederle </PERSON>, a popular actor. `` We must find them.'' <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> has offered to play some sort of transitional role, but has made it plain he is not eager to be the missing clapper in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s liberty bell. Late Saturday night, he emerged from a dinner, haggard. `` Are you going into politics?'' he was asked. `` I'm going to bed,'' he replied.
