<HEAD>Endorsing European Change Easier Than Keeping Pace with It</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> are finding it easier to endorse political change in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> than to deal with the consequences. After a summit meeting in which both leaders envisioned an end to East-West rivalry, they face the considerably more difficult task of redefining their respective military alliances without upsetting a balance of power established through 40 years of Cold War. For <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the assignment is especially tricky. He seeks to preserve his <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact alliance at the same time that its hard-line communist regimes are being swept aside. During the post-summit news conference, a <LOCATION> Czechoslovakian </LOCATION> journalist pointedly asked whether he had renounced the <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> doctrine used to justify the 1968 Soviet invasion of that country as it began to tip Westward. `` Every nation is an independent entity in world politics and every people has the right to choose its own destiny, the destiny of its own state,'' the Soviet leader replied. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s response underscored the diminishing role _ and perhaps ability _ of the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> to control the political avalanche in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` No one can avoid this evolutionary process,'' he said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, following <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in response to the Czechoslovakian question, praised the Soviet leader for the reforms he has started in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and its allies. However, the president is not as eager to claim, as the Soviet leader had at the joint news conference, that the `` epoch of the cold war'' is over. On Monday, after he briefed <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said: `` Is the Cold War raging like it was before, in the times of the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> blockade? Absolutely not. But if I signal to you there's no Cold War, then they'll say, ` Well, what are you doing with troops in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>?''' Both leaders say they want to preserve the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact to maintain stability, but want to conclude an agreement by late 1990 to cut troops in Central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, withdrawing 30,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and 325,000 Soviet soldiers. The memory of <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which invaded many <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> members during World War II, still looms large in the European equation. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has expressed concern about a proposal last week by West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> for a confederation of East and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Soviet officials say <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has never renounced its claims to the pre-war German borders, which included parts of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> sought to assuage those Soviet fears by reaffirming <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for the 1975 <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> Accords, which were signed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and 33 other nations and `` spells out a concept of permanent borders.'' The <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> accords, said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, `` summed up the results of the Second World War and consolidated the results of the war. ... And the reality is such that we have today's <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> with two German states.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> reiterated the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position that any move toward the reunification of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> will have to be gradual and respect the rights of people on both sides of the present border to self-determination. At the same time, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made it clear that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will keep its troops in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> as long as <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies want them there. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will remain a <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> power, and that means that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will stay engaged in the future of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and in our common defense,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. To cope with Soviet concerns about <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> unified outside the postwar alliance strucure and to keep pace with the changes in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has accepted Polish proposals to restructure the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> should do the same, he said. `` They should not remain military alliances, but rather military-political alliances and later on, just political alliances, so that their nature would change in accordance with the changes on the continent,'' he said.
</TEXT>
