<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Zeid </PERSON> <PERSON> Bin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaker </PERSON> resigned Monday and was replaced by <PERSON> Mudar </PERSON> <PERSON> Badran </PERSON>, who has held the office twice before and is sympathetic to Islamic fundamentalists. King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> told <PERSON> Badran </PERSON> to concentrate on improving <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s dismal economy situation and to support the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Bin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaker </PERSON>'s resignation had been expected following parliamentary elections last month, the first nationwide balloting in 22 years. He took office in April after the resignation of <PERSON> Zaid </PERSON> <PERSON> Rifai </PERSON> and formed a transitional government for the purpose of preparing for the elections. The king assigned the outgoing <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> to continue its duties until <PERSON> Badran </PERSON> forms a new one. `` I ask you to work with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and to support the steadfastness of our brothers, the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> in their occupied territories,'' <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> said in a letter to <PERSON> Badran </PERSON>, the former chief of the royal court. The monarch stressed the importance of increasing the kingdom's foreign currency reserves and maintaining the Jordanian dinar's purchasing Since late last year, the dinar's value against other currencies has fallen sharply under the pressure of foreign debts of more than $ 8.3 billion. Riots triggered by price increases of 10 percent to 50 percent for food and fuel led to riots that killed nine people in April and led to <PERSON> Rifai </PERSON>'s resignation. Royal palace officials said naming of a new Cabinet might be delayed because of disputes among potential new ministers over the assignment of portfolios. The palace officials said the new Cabinet would include some former ministers, some members of the royally appointed senate and some deputies elected Nov. 8. According to one royal palace source, the disputes stem from three Moslem Brotherhood deputies who were assigned portfolios `` which they did not accept.'' The source did not explain what chairs they were assigned but he said they were seeking the portfolios of education, higher education and Islamic religious affairs. The Moslem Brotherhood, which won 25 seats in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, campaigned to impose stricter Islamic laws and improve social welfare benefits. There are nearly three dozen deputies in the 80-seat Parliament with Islamic leanings. <PERSON> Badran </PERSON> is known to sympathize with extremist Moslem factions, including the Moslem Brotherhood. The November elections were the first nationwide poll since 1967 when <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> captured the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> last year renounced <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s claim to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> in favor of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Badran </PERSON>, who graduated from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Damscus </ORGANIZATION> in 1957 with a law degree, served as prime minister as well as defense and foreign affairs minister in 1976-79 and 1980-84. During both of <PERSON> Badran </PERSON>'s terms, <LOCATION> Jordanian </LOCATION> relations with <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> deteriorated, first because Syrian alleged <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> was supporting Moslem Brotherhood activists seeking to topple Syrian President <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON>. The countries reconciled in 1979 after <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON> j