 on <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. He said he would like <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to use his influence to `` facilitate democratic change'' in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>. The sources said the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> now have about 38 MI-17's in their inventory. The MI-17 is an advanced version of the MI-8 helicopter and is more easily adaptable than the MI-8 for use as a gunship. Since there are already many MI-17's in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, one official said the new shipment could not necessarily be considered a provocation. The official said the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> already have enough MI-17's and described the additional helicopters as unnecessary. He added that the delivery probably had been in the planning stage for months and that it may have been a coincidence that the ship carrying the helicopters left <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> just before the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> summit. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, citing intelligence reports, said the shipment left <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> aboard the vessel <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Ilyich </PERSON>. The MI-17 delivery to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials see it, appears to be more closely related to the internal situation in that country than to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. National elections are set for Feb. 25 and the Sandinista government is angry that the Contra rebels continue to operate not only inside <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> but also remain deployed at base camps in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. Nicaraguan President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> and four other Central American presidents called in August for the demobilization of the rebels by this Tuesday, but that deadline will pass with the resistance forces still intact. The