<HEAD>Minority, Female Promotions Upheld</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court on Monday upheld <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>'s agreement to hire and promote women and minorities in the white male-dominated Fire Department. In a 3-0 ruling, the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> rejected a union claim that the plan violated the rights of white men by setting numerical goals for minority and female employment and by requiring the promotion of 33 minority firefighters. The agreement, approved in a consent decree by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> <PERSON> Patel </PERSON> in June 1988, `` is fundamentally fair, adequate and reasonable,'' said the opinion by Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. The court noted the department had no blacks until 1955 and no women until 1987, and the city's hiring and promotional tests for firefighters had repeatedly been found discriminatory from 1970 to 1987. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said the decree met the standards for race - and sex-based remedies set by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>: a `` manifest imbalance'' between representation of groups in the Fire Department and the population, and the fashioning of a plan that does not unnecessarily hurt whites and males The decree, which ended 18 years of lawsuits by minorities and women, was challenged by Firefighters Union Local 798, with the support of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. As the litigation neared a climax, a swastika was found in the office of two minority firefighters in December 1987. <PERSON> Patel </PERSON> pronounced the department `` out of control'' and ordered top officials to enforce rules against racial and sexual harassment under threat of contempt of court. Shortly afterward, Fire Chief <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Phipps </PERSON> resigned. The appeals court upheld <PERSON> Patel </PERSON>'s order in Monday's ruling, saying there was `` ample evidence of foot-dragging'' by the department in enforcing its rules against harassment. When the decree on hiring and promotions was signed, the department had 225 minorities and seven women on its staff of 1,100. The plan sets long-term goals of 40 percent minorities and 10 percent women in the department, and goals of 55 percent minority hiring and 10 percent female hiring through 1994. The appeals court ordered the plan modified to eliminate the hiring standards before 1994 if the long-term goals were met by then. The plan also requires the city to prepare new, unbiased examinations for hiring and promotion, and to promote 33 minority firefighters to the rank of lieutenant. An additional 48 promotions are optional, of which 12 must be minorities. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> rejected the union's argument that the plan was discriminatory by requiring the promotion of minorities but not of whites. No evidence was presented of past discrimination against whites, he said.
