decade to the Salvadoran government in the war, which has killed 71,000 people, 1,000 of them in the latest fighting. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> likened the raids and arrests to the internment of Japanese-Americans during World War II. `` I'm not condoning it. But in times like these of great emotion and great anger, things like this happen. Even in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, with all its guarantees, it happened,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. `` There are a series of indications of a climate of persecution,'' said <PERSON> Monsignor </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregorio </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON>, auxiliary bishop of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, after Mass on Sunday. `` Not only against personnel of the Catholic church, but against many people who try to help the most humble and the most poor.'' `` It appears that the military authorities, in their quest to restore order, have adopted as their criteria the saying, ` Think the worst, and you'll be right,''' he said. The climate of war and fear has tinged even jokes. One goes like this: Two soldiers are patrolling the streets 10 minutes before the beginning of the nightly curfew. They pass a man walking quickly in the opposite direction. One soldier turns around and fatally shoots the man. `` Why'd you do that?'' asks his companion. `` I know that guy. He lives 20 minutes from here.''
