<HEAD>Jury Selection Begins in Pit Bull Murder Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the first case of its kind, the owner of a pit bull dog went on trial Monday in the murder of a toddler mauled after wandering into the dog's path while, prosecutors say, it was guarding 243 marijuana plants. Jury selection began in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Superior </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Court </LOCATION> for <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Berry </PERSON>, 39, of <LOCATION> Morgan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> is charged with second-degree murder for the June 13, 1987, death of his 2-year-old neighbor, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Soto </PERSON>, who died of severe blood loss after being attacked by the <PERSON> Berry </PERSON>'s pit bull named <PERSON> Willy </PERSON>. <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> also faces felony marijuana cultivation charges. According to the prosecutor and the <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the trial marks the first time in this country that a pet owner has been charged with murder because of an animal's actions. Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanderson </PERSON> acknowledged there is no evidence of malice or intent to kill young <PERSON> Soto </PERSON>, but said the prosecution is based on the theory of implied malice. That allows a murder conviction for someone whose actions show wanton disregard for human life. `` What we have is a guy who raises a dog that is bred for aggressiveness and to be a combatant,'' <PERSON> Sanderson </PERSON> said during <PERSON> Berry </PERSON>'s arraignment two years ago. `` And, knowing the dog's propensity, he places him in an area accessible to all _ including children. During a search of <PERSON> Berry </PERSON>'s home, authorities said they found several publications on illegal dog fighting, and a dog-sized conditioning treadmill. A gag order was issued last month, barring both sides from discussing the case. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Soto </PERSON>'s father, <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON>, said he and his wife had left <PERSON> James </PERSON> playing with new toy trucks on their back patio while they went shopping at garage sales. When they returned, the father said he found their son being `` torn apart'' by the pit bull after apparently wandering through an open gate and into the unfenced yard of their neighbor. The child never regained consciousness. At least 157 people have died from dog attacks nationwide in the past 10 years, 70 percent of them under the age of 10, according to the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. But of those cases, the <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> said only one owner has been convicted of a major felony. <PERSON> Hayward </PERSON> <PERSON> Turnipseed </PERSON> of <LOCATION> De </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kalb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, was convicted of involuntary manslaughter and sentenced to five years in prison after three of his pit bulls killed a 4-year-old boy in 1987. <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> has contended that he has been singled out because his dog attacked a child at a time when the breed was the center of considerable negative publicity. `` I think a murder rap is overdoing it by a lot,'' said <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadish </PERSON>, a law professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>. `` If this is the highest form of crime, then what do we do with the hired killer or the serial rapist?'' <PERSON> Kadish </PERSON> and other lega experts have speculated that <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> was charged with second-degree murder in an effort to force him to plead guilty to involuntary manslaughter instead. <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> faces 15 years to life in prison if convicted. While <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> goes on trial, his dog, <PERSON> Willy </PERSON>, remains at the <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION> animal shelter. He has not been destroyed because he is considered evidence in the case, and he is described as a friendly and affectionate dog. But shelter spokeswoman <PERSON> Stacy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> said <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> nevertheless will be destroyed at the conclusion of the legal battle.
</TEXT>
