<HEAD>Monday's East Bloc Developments at a Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Monday's East bloc developments:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CZECHOSLOVAKIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 More than 150,000 demonstrators filled Wenceslas Square, rejecting the new Communist-dominated government and demanding free elections. The opposition called for a second general strike on Dec. 11 if there is no new government by Sunday. Thousands of tourists from <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> freely visited the West for the first time in decades after the government lifted most travel restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EAST GERMANY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 East Germans outraged by the corruption of ex-leaders tried to storm secret police offices to make sure the evidence was protected. Prosecutors blocked access by the ousted officials to the evidence. Premier <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Modrow </PERSON> emerged as the leading political figure one day after the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership resigned. He led a three-member delegation to the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact summit in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>POLAND</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> opened a bureau in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, its second in the Soviet bloc, and launched discussions with Polish state radio on exchanging programming. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poland </ORGANIZATION> devalued the zloty by 9.5 percent, continuing a drive to create a convertible currency that would encourage Western investment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ELSEWHERE:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 _ The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for the first time jointly condemned the 1968 Soviet-led invasion of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> that crushed the `` Prague Spring'' reforms. The <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact nations, meeting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, said the invasion constitituted `` interference in the internal affairs of a sovereign <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>.'' _ President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, said it's too early to proclaim an end to the Cold War, but added that <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s acceptance of sweeping reform in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> `` absolutely mandates new thinking'' by the West He also endorsed a cautious and measured approach to reunifying <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. _ <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said his weekend meeting with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> gave the two leaders a chance to cement a personal relationship, although `` it was n't all sweetness and light.'' _ The Czechoslavak journal <ORGANIZATION> Lidove </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Noviny </ORGANIZATION>, which is associated with the democratic opposition, was awarded a $ 10,000 grant from a group of Western press associations that have established a new project to assist East bloc media.
