<HEAD>Central America Summit to be Held in Costa Rica</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The next summit meeting of five <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents will be held in <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> Dec. 10-12, sources close to President <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> said Monday. The meeting, which had been scheduled for <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, probably will be in <LOCATION> Heredia </LOCATION>, nine miles from the capital of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, according to the sources who spoke on condition they not be identified. Plans to hold the summit in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> were canceled because <LOCATION> Salvadoran </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> refused to go to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> suspended relations with <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> last week after two planes, allegedly smuggling arms from <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> to leftist rebels in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, were found in Salvadoran territory. One crashed and the four crewmen perished, and the other was burned by its crew at a landing strip because the craft was out of fuel, according to Salvadoran officials. The presidents of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, at their meeting last August in <LOCATION> Tela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, agreed to demobilize the Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras, by Dec. 5. Next week's meeting is supposed to review the relocation of the Contras, thousands of whom live in camps across the border in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. Most of the Contras, who have been fighting the Sandinista government for eight years, refuse to disband and be relocated until after <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s elections, scheduled for February. Nicaraguan President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, who had insisted that the meeting be held in his country, relented over the weekend and agreed to meet in <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, the sources reported. They said there were offers to hold the summit in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, but <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> insisted it be held in the region. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> has said all the presidents except <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> agreed on <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> as a replacement site for <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. `` All the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> foreign ministers are pressuring that the summit be held in a hotel with conveniences, not only for the presidents, but also for the press,'' said a Nicaraguan diplomat who asked not to be identified. The Costa Rican location most frequently mentioned is the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insitute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Heredia </LOCATION>. Also attending the meeting will be <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION>, and representatives of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>, the Nicaraguan diplomat said.
