<HEAD>With AM-Bush-NATO Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Economists Applaud Efforts To Help Gorbachev Restructure Society</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economists and business leaders expressed general support Monday for President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s actions at the <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> summit to support Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s `` perestroika'' restructuring efforts `` <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> is a long-run affair with all kinds of great promise,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` One should be cautious, but there are great hopes and optimism that a new era is dawning.'' <PERSON> Dwayne </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON>, chief executive of the agricultural giant, <ORGANIZATION> Archer-Daniels-Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, said that `` unleashing the forces of free-enterprise ca n't be anything but beneficial.'' The analysts were asked their views of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s statements and actions of recent days in connection with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s efforts to revamp an ailing economy. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> lent encouragement to that effort. But during a news conference in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> Monday following his briefing of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> leaders, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said chances were `` slim and none'' that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> would be invited to join the world's seven richest countries at their economic summit meeting next July. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the Soviets need to do much more to reform their government-controlled economic system before they could be considered for inclusion in the annual economic summits attended by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. The next meeting is scheduled for early July in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> had sent a letter to the world leaders at last summer's meeting in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, asking to be included in the annual talks But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told reporters he did not think it likely that the Soviets would be participating in next year's summit, saying he saw `` two chances _ slim and none _ for that particular meeting.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that what was most important now was for Communist countries trying to transform their economies to get expertise in how market-based systems work. `` We have got to understand -LRB- <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s -RRB- dilemma. They have not had a market economy,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` It is important that not just the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> but other countries in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> understand the market economies, understand the dynamism of the economic systems that join -LRB- the seven economic summit -RRB- countries together.'' The president announced several initiatives at his weekend meeting with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> aimed at helping to integrate the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> into the world economy. He pledged to remove high <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tariffs levied on Soviet imports once the Soviets approve legislation allowing free emigration. He also promised to support observer status for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the 97-member international organization that governs world trade. Observer status would not automatically entitle the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to various favorable trade concessions granted full <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> members, but it would provide Soviet officials with first-hand knowledge of the deliberations occurring in the organization. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had previously opposed Soviet requests for observer status, maintaining that the Soviet system was incompatible with <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>'s free-trade principles. <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s promise to lower tariffs on Soviet goods following approval of the liberalized emigration law should foster reciprocal actions by the Soviets to purchase more American goods, including farm products. Before the farm trade restrictions imposed by then-President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> in retaliation for the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> invasion of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, American farmers supplied 70 percent of the agricultural products imported by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> share of the Soviet agricultural market is now 45 percent. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, an economist with <PERSON> DRI-McGraw </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, said that it was essential for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to provide some specific proposals to bolster the reforms <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is trying to institute in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` If perestroika fails, it is going to fail because of economics,'' <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> said. `` We have much to lose by the Russians failing. We should be helping them any way we can.''
