<HEAD>Everyone's Happy in St. Louis Newspaper Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sun </LOCATION> has grabbed more than 100,000 readers a day in its first two months of publication, but has n't drawn readers away from the established <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Dispatch </ORGANIZATION>, executives of the two newspapers said Monday. In fact, <ORGANIZATION> Post-Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> officials sounded almost grateful to the upstart Sun, which is the newest newspaper in the country. `` I do firmly believe that the <PERSON> Post-Dispatch </PERSON> is a much better newspaper today than it was a year ago,'' <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Penniman </PERSON> IV, publisher of the <PERSON> Post-Dispatch </PERSON> and vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Pulitzer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said at an annual editors meeting. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lipman </PERSON>, managing editor of the <PERSON> Post-Dispatch </PERSON>, said the new competition has accelerated changes that were in the works at the 111-year-old newspaper and given it a jolt of adrenalin. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Post-Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> feels 10 years younger. And we're going to continue feeling young and being useful and still be a lot of fun,'' he said. The Sun, which debuted Sept. 25, has been averaging about 107,000 circulation for its first two months, while the <PERSON> Post-Dispatch </PERSON>'s circulation has remained steady at 378,000 daily and 565,000 on Sunday. The <ORGANIZATION> Post-Dispatch </ORGANIZATION>'s Saturday newspaper has increased its circulation about 3 percent to 348,000 since the Sun began appearing with an expanded Saturday paper that costs $ 1 compared to 25 cents for the Saturday Post-Dispatch. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingersoll </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, the Sun's editor-in-chief and chairman of its parent company, <ORGANIZATION> Ingersoll </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said he expected the Sun to turn a profit by the end of 1990. However, he said profits wo n't be as high as originally projected because the newspaper is attracting more home subscribers and fewer newsstand buyers than expected. Home subscribers pay less. Ingersoll brushed aside talk of a `` newspaper war'' in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. `` We look on it as a competition, which is something different than a war,'' he said. Before the debut of the Sun, the Post-Dispatch had been without competition since the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe-Democrat </ORGANIZATION> folded in Oct. 1986.
