<HEAD>Skinner Sees High Drug Use In Transportation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> predicted Monday that random drug testing will reveal an `` alarming amount of drug usage'' among people responsible for the safety of land, air and sea transportation. Rules begin going into effect in two weeks that require random and other drug tests for millions of airline, railroad, mass transit, bus company, boat, trucking company and pipeline employees. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said that where court orders do not stop the testing, companies must comply with the new rule. Several suits have been filed by workers to stop the federally imposed program. Startup dates for the testing vary by modes of transportation. The secretary said he has set up a group in his office to monitor progress of the testing, while agencies dealing with aviation, railroads and other modes would each oversee industries they cover. `` Once they begin the testing, I think we'll see an alarming amount of drug use and positive testing in safety-related jobs,'' said <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> at a session with reporters. He said he expects the results to justify the high priority the administration has given the program. Random drug tests in the military showed high drug use in the first few months, he said. Ten percent of tested <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> personnel showed positive, but the incidence has since dropped to 2 percent because of the testing, he said. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said the government would not be lenient with companies that do not make an effort to begin drug-testing programs. `` I do n't want to be unfair,'' he said, but `` the time has come where we've got to move forward on this testing. We're not going to sit here and tell somebody who is required by law or regulation to conduct the test that they can just wait until they are ready.'' Possible action against employers, including civil penalties or withholding of federal funds, varies by transportation modes. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said that `` with rare exception'' airlines have submitted drug-testing plans that have been approved. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> extended the August deadline after several smaller airlines failed to submit their programs. The secretary said he had been told by more than one mass transit operator to expect high rates of drug usage when the testing begins, possibly significantly higher than the 10 percent found in the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>. Results should vary in different parts of the country and in different modes of transportation, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said, but added, `` I know it's a major problem all over this country.'' Asked what effect high drug use might have on the continuation of transportation services, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said, `` If the percentages were 40 percent, it would be devastating. If it were 5 percent, they could probably work their way through it.''
