<HEAD>Soil Erosion Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sheet and rill erosion on cropland decreased by a half ton per acre nationwide between 1982 and 1987, dropping from 4.3 tons to 3.8 tons per acre a year, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. However, wind erosion on cropland increased 0.1 ton per acre to 3.3 tons per acre a year, said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inventory </ORGANIZATION> report from the department's soil conservation service. According to the data, sheet and rill erosion nationwide totals 1.6 billion tons per year and wind erosion 1.4 billion tons annually. The survey `` reveals impressive gains for soil conservation,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION>, a Washington-based non-profit environmental research and publishing organization. But the research also shows that soil erosion is still a serious problem, it said in a statement released Monday. `` From everything we know about land use in the mid-1970s, erosion conditions worsened with the onset of the export boom,'' said <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, vice president of the center. He said analysis of the survey data may show that the improvement in erosion control is due substantially to massive idling of cropland under government programs between 1984 and 1987. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the report does not reflect the work under way on about 140 million acres of highly erodible land as part of the conservation provisions of the 1985 farm law. Rural nonfederal land now totals 1.4 billion acres. Of this 422.8 million acres are cropland, 401.7 million acres are rangeland, 394.4 million acres are forestland and 59.9 million aces are in minor land uses, the survey says.
