<HEAD>Congressman Says Study Reveals Inconsistency In FAA Exemptions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government has granted hundreds of airline pilots medical exemptions to fly but has not used similar exemptions to allow pilots to fly past the mandatory retirement age of 60, a congressional study released Monday said. Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roybal </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., who released the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> study, said the study reveals an inconsistency in <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> rules that he said have kept some of the most qualified and experienced pilots from operating large commercial airliners The report says the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> granted 1,301 exemptions to requirements for medical certificates 1960 through 1988. It said that among the 40,000 active air transport pilots, 605 now have `` special issuance'' medical certificates for alcoholism and 104 for cardiovascular conditions. `` Allowing such pilots to continue flying, but excluding a 60-year-old pilot in perfect health, clearly does not make sense,'' said <PERSON> Roybal </PERSON>, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Aging. The report said none of 67 petitions by 418 pilots asking for exemptions for pilots over 60 has been granted by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>, which has said it adopted the rule for safety. Some of the applications are still pending. Pilots over 60 can fly commercial jets with fewer than 30 passengers and a payload under 7,500 pounds but must retire as captains or copilots of large airliners. <PERSON> Roybal </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> should reconsider the basis for its age-60 rule, which went into effect in 1959 and has been challenged by pilot groups and others over the years. The report by the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, which is <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' investigative arm, summarized legal challenges to the rule, legislative efforts and the position of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> and pilots but made no recommendation. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, representing pilots, earlier opposed the rule but since 1980 has backed the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> position, saying there has been no study that provides a way of determining which pilots over 60 are fit to fly safely. Opponents of the rule include the <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Owners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>.
