<HEAD>Palestinian Leaders Escape Trial for Security Reasons</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Uprising Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Security considerations convinced the government not to investigate and try two prominent Palestinians identified as uprising leaders by an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> legislator and court documents, officials said Monday. <PERSON> Tzahi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanegbi </PERSON>, the legislator, alleged in a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal that philosophy professor <PERSON> Sari </PERSON> <PERSON> Nusseibeh </PERSON> and the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Radwan </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayyash </PERSON>, handled uprising funds and wrote leaflets urging escalation of the 2-year-old rebellion. <LOCATION> Hanegbi </LOCATION>, of Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s conservative <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc, quoted documents submitted to a military court at <LOCATION> Lod </LOCATION> in May that called <PERSON> Nusseibeh </PERSON> a paymaster of the uprising in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, responsible for distributing <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> funds and publishing uprising literature. He claimed <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayyash </PERSON> represented <ORGANIZATION> Fatah </ORGANIZATION>, the guerrilla group of <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Palestinie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> chief, in the underground Unified National Leadership of the Uprising and was responsible for several leaflets, army radio reported. Neither has been charged and <LOCATION> Hanegbi </LOCATION> demanded both men be tried, the national news agency <ORGANIZATION> Itim </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Nili </PERSON> <PERSON> Arad </PERSON> of the st