<HEAD>Dubcek: `You Cannot Suppress an Idea'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, ousted in disgrace as <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader after the Soviet-led invasion in 1968, praised his countrymen's struggle for democracy and said, `` You can not suppress an idea.'' <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> broadcast on Monday an interview with <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Bratislava </LOCATION>. The 67-year-old leader of the `` Prague Spring'' reforms said, `` An idea is going to survive within people's conscience.'' He spoke of the 17 years he lived in forced obscurity after being removed from office in 1969 and stripped of party membership in 1970. `` They wanted to totally isolate me. I was followed everywhere,'' he said. `` I had to keep my circle of friends small to protect them. Maybe they thought I could n't take it psychologically but I could. It's been a hard life but we are still here.'' <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> was relegated to work as a minor forestry official in the Slovak capital of <LOCATION> Bratislava </LOCATION> and barred from travel. The restrictions were relaxed after Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> in April 1987. Reforms instituted by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> have surged like a tidal wave through the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc and on Nov. 24 <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s hard-line <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> government resigned under public pressure. Tens of thousands of people cheered <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>'s Wenceslas Square on his triumphant return to the capital. `` To speak in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> gave me a deep sense of satisfaction,'' he said Monday. `` Twenty years ago their parents cheered me. Now these children are doing the same and supporting the same ideas.'' He said many of the democratic reforms being demanded now were part of his 1968 plans. `` There was no internal power willing to stop the ` <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> Spring,' we were suppressed by external force,'' he said, speaking through an interpreter. `` The basic idea is the same now. You can not suppress an idea. An idea is going to survive within people's conscience.'' Thousands of Czechoslovaks demonstrated Monday, protesting the composition of the new Communist-dominated government. <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> was asked if he might become president and he said, `` For the presidency it's up to the people to decide.'' <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> received virtually complete vindication Monday when a <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> summit meeting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> condemned the 1968 invasion as `` interference in the internal affairs of a sovereign'' <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>.
