<HEAD>`Up Against It,' A New Musical, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There is n't a messier musical in town than `` Up Against It,'' an apt title for this chaotic song and dance adaptation of an unproduced screenplay originally written by <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Orton </PERSON> for the Beatles. The musical, which opened Monday at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shakespeare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION>, defeats a lot of people _ particularly a slew of talented performers such as <PERSON> Alison </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON>, <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Casnoff </PERSON> and <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> <PERSON> Dibuono </PERSON>, director <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> and <PERSON> Orton </PERSON> himself. Only hints of <PERSON> Orton </PERSON>'s wicked humor show through in this flat-footed and tuneless version of his story adapted for the stage by <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> with music and lyrics by rock star <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Rundgren </PERSON>. <PERSON> Orton </PERSON>, the iconoclastic English playwright who was murdered by his lover in 1967, apparently fashioned a satiric tale about the adventures of two British scamps and a subsequent war between the sexes. In the musical, the battle takes place after a group of radical men have assassinated the female prime minister. She is replaced by another, even tougher woman, played with relentless assurance by the booming <PERSON> Dibuono </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>' scattershot book takes on religion, the rich, right-wing politicians, sexual stereotyping, the military and all points in between. The low point of the musical occurs when the men dress up as women to infiltrate a political rally held by the prime minister. The number is called _ what else _ `` Life Is a Drag'' and it is as hard to watch as it is to listen to. Most of <PERSON> Rundgren </PERSON>'s score is a disappointment. Except for a fine ballad entitled `` Parallel Lines,'' it is remarkably conventional, blandly at odds with the outrageousness of the story being told on stage. <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> has directed the show at a furious pace, and <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Muller </PERSON>'s choreography is equally athletic. Nothing stops for very long, although the musical numbers have a way of numbing the story line rather than advancing the plot. What <PERSON> Orton </PERSON> and the Beatles would have done with `` Up Against It'' is a tantalizing question. There are hints of such Beatle movies as `` A Hard Day's Night'' and `` Help!'' in some of the musical's more frantic posturings. But you would be better off to rent videos of those classics than sit through `` Up Against It.''
