to the 13th always falling on Friday in months beginning on Monday, and
to Christmas always falling on Monday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW UNDERWOOD, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rancher <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Raba </PERSON> figures the present calendar switches around too much on the number of days in a month, so he's drawn up a new plan where there'd be 28 days each month _ all 13 of them. `` I have n't had hardly anybody that did n't agree with me'' said <ORGANIZATION> Raba </ORGANIZATION>, 78. `` But I might not live long enough to see the change.'' His calendar would be easy to understand and remember, <ORGANIZATION> Raba </ORGANIZATION> says. Thirteen 28-day months equals 364 days. Making up for the 365th day is simple. Just create a 48-hour New Year's Day. Leap Year every four years also would have an extra 48-hour day, wiping out the current Feb. 29. The current calendar, adopted in 1582, has 12 months with either 28, 29, 30 or 31 days. The Raba calendar would mean fixed-date holidays would always be on the same day of the week. Every month would start on Monday, which is the first day of <ORGANIZATION> Raba </ORGANIZATION>'s weeks. The current names of months and days would remain, but the 13th month would need a name. <ORGANIZATION> Raba </ORGANIZATION> said he has suggested the calendar to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, former Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Janklow </PERSON>, current Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mickelson </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, Canadian officials and others. `` All the answers I got, they thought it made sense and was good,'' he said. `` But most did n't know if we was quite ready for it yet. ... They all agreed that we're due for a change somehow.''
