<HEAD>Hope to Avert Big Oil Spill by Refloating Tanker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HERZLIYA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Divers managed Monday to block most leaks in an oil tanker that sank after developing engine troubles and officials hoped to refloat the vessel before its cargo causes an ecological disaster. Up to 60 tons of the ship's 660 tons of heavy oil have polluted the waters off this <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> resort since the Israeli-owned <PERSON> Eyal </PERSON> went down Thursday after it stalled because of engine problems and was swamped by high seas. The 150-foot-long tanker, used for refueling other vessels, has been resting on its stern with just the tip of the bow above the surface. It is 600 yards offshore. <PERSON> Ami </PERSON> <PERSON> Barad </PERSON>, head of the salvage operation, said divers sealed all leaks except some `` very small'' ones Monday and hoped the vessel could be refloated before it breaks up. Heavy waves prevented a floating crane needed for the operation from reaching the site Monday.
</TEXT>
