<FIRST>r a AM-AIDS-Churches     12-04 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Churches,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Call for Non-Judgmental Care of AIDS Sufferers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Church leaders Monday called on religious individuals and organizations to provide non-judgmental and compassionate care and support to people suffering from AIDS. The leaders also called on churches to develop accurate and comprehensive AIDS education materials `` in a context that promotes individual self-esteem, teaches the fundamental goodness of human sexuality and supports the integrity of responsible and caring intimate relationships.'' The comments were included in a consensus statement on appropriate religious responses to the AIDS epidemic adopted Monday by about 130 clergy and lay leaders from Christian, Jewish, Unitarian and interfaith groups during a conference at the Carter Presidential Center. The religious community has a responsibility `` to assure that all whose lives are affected by the epidemic will have access to compassion, non-judgmental care, respect, support and assistance,'' the statement said. The Right Rev. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Theuner </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on AIDS and bishop of the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diocese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION>, said church leaders must overcome a perception among AIDS sufferers that religious people view the disease as the `` wraith of God'' for an immoral lifestyle. `` Some think that the religious community believes AIDS is a judgment of God. But by and large the religious community does not and those of us in a position of leadership need to convey that more forcefully,'' he said. The consensus statement said churches have a responsibility to `` transform public attitudes and policies so that adequate care and appropriate preventative measures will be available for all people in need.'' The group called on President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` to demonstrate moral and political leadership'' by protecting people with AIDS from discrimination, by expanding drug-treatment programs to all who choose them, by expediting the experimental treatment approval process, by expanding home-care programs for AIDS sufferers and by encouraging strict confidentiality of AIDS tests. The statement said foreigners should be allowed to visit or become citizens of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> if they are eligible to do so, regardless of whether they have AIDS. The group also advocated comprehensive programs for drug users `` including the distribution of AIDS prevention information and materials including bleach for the sterilization of hypodermic needles.'' AIDS _ acquired immune deficiency syndrome _ is a deadly disease which attacks the body's immune system, crippling its ability to ward off infections that are not a problem for most people, such as a rare pneumonia and a rare skin cancer. The latest federal public health figures indicate 112,241 people have been reported with AIDS since 1981 and 59 percent of them have die from it. No one is known to have recovered. Sixty percent of the total cases have involved homosexual or bisexual males, 20 percent were intravenous drug abusers and another 7 percent were both drug abusers who were also homosexual males. Forty-three percent of all cases involved minorities. In a reference to those statistics, the group said in its consensus statement that, `` Because barriers among us based on religion, race, class, gender and sexual orientation that continue to generate fear, persecution and violence are intensified by the -LRB- AIDS epidemic -RRB-, we call upon all sectors of our society, particularly our faith communities, to adopt as highest priority the elimination of racism, classism, sexism and homophobia.'' The conference was cosponsored by the AIDS <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interfaith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interfaith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AIDS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> and The Carter Center of <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Among the groups represented were the <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the African <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Synagogue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congregations </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Unitarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Universalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the Baptist General Convention of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fellowship </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>.
