<HEAD>Elizabeth Ashley: Free Spirit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Mary C Brown,' with no period, is CQ in 12th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Talking with <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> is a grand adventure. She has fierce energy and a jumpy, bawdy sense of humor. Her sentences go every which way but loose, full of digressions, asides and hard sayings. Such as: `` Football is an absolute metaphor for life. If you want nice, clean, let's - pretend sports, watch Technically, that has nothing to do with her latest venture. But it's the thought that counts. Her latest venture, on cable TV Thursday, is an Arts & amp; Entertainment version of <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>'s `` The Rope.'' She, her fellow Tony-award winners <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Len </PERSON> <PERSON> Cariou </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> co-star in it. One of four adaptations of one-act plays by Pulitzer Prize-winning playwrights, Thursday's one-hour drama is, in the <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> custom, a poetic, bitter tale _ in this case one about a family torn by despair. She has known that world of well-scrivened gloom before. But it proved a particularly good deal in 1974. Then, several years after a string of so-so TV movies and a busted marriage to actor <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Peppard </PERSON>, whom she refers to only as `` the husband,'' she went back to theater. It was part of a process of starting all over again, says <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>, who'd been hailed as an actress of great promise when she won Broadway's <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> award in 1962 as the bouncy, nubile daughter in `` Take Her, She's Mine.'' Twelve years later, she says, `` the American Shakesepeare Festival and <PERSON> Tennessee </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> saved me from being a third-rate television actress today with ` Cat on a Hot Tin Roof.''' In that <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> revival, she was acclaimed for her interpretation of <PERSON> Maggie </PERSON>, the Southern beauty married to an alcoholic. Herself a Southern beauty to whom time has been tender, <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>, 50, was born in <LOCATION> Ocala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and raised in <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. She is a veteran, she says, of one semester at <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. She came to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> at 18 to model and appear in commercials. Then she studied acting at the Neighborhood Playhouse, paying the way by waiting tables and playing guitar, `` plunking a few chords and singing your odd songs.'' Possessed of a husky, well-modulated voice, she is not thought of as a singer. Still, she once appeared in a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> production of a short-lived musical by her friend <PERSON> Dory </PERSON> <PERSON> Previn </PERSON>, `` <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> C </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> and the Hollywood Sign.'' Her own assessment: `` I'm not your best singer of show tunes. I'm a pretty good country singer, though, and I was a great rock' n' roll screamer.'' She said all this and more when interviewed in her favorite bistro, where she periodically lit a cigarette and cheerfully denounced both yuppies and no-smoking fiends who've ruined most bistros. Her life, which includes a son, <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Peppard </PERSON>, now 21, has taken a goodly measure of ups and downs. Ten years ago, after she'd taken a few years off to go sailing and ponder the cosmos and such, it was down time She had all the goodies, she says _ a house in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION>, two lofts in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, a couple of costly foreign cars. But there was only $ 83 in the till. She rented out the house, sold the cars, and awaited developments. She got a call for a Broadway part. It was as the chain-smoking psychiatrist in what proved a hit, `` Agnes of God.'' `` That was God kissing me on the cheek,'' she says. `` The second time around.'' <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>, who this year filmed an <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> movie, `` Orleans,'' and starts off-Broadway rehearsals next month on `` When She Danced,'' about dancer <PERSON> Isadora </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>, spent 14 months on Broadway in `` Agnes of God.'' Then, she says, she spent 40 more weeks on the road, touring in the play. More than a few actors hate touring. Not <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>. `` I like the road,'' she says. `` It's great to be in a Broadway hit and a long run. But they know where you are then, and people start calling you and asking you to do things like'' _ she laughed and winced _ `` lunch.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: SAME TIME, THIS YEAR _ <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, whose syndicated shout show got axed last summer due to fleeing sponsors and declining ratings, returned to TV Monday. He's back bellowing on cable, <ORGANIZATION> CBNC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Showdown,'' where his co-host, who also is a co-bellower, is <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> columnist. Monday's scheduled premiere threatened a discussion with a <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> city councilman of suspects' and victims' rights. But it often degenerated into hostile co-host babble, with <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> twice calling <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> `` sick.'' <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> in turn accused his black colleague of being hung up on racial issues, then sneered that `` I even get my makeup put on darker so we'll match.'' For the record, the new show has a studio audience and <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> now wears a gold ring in his left ear lobe.
</TEXT>
