<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv05   12-04 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 05,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tuesday, Dec. 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>Equity Rich, Cash Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As much as $ 750 billion of equity is held by homeowners who are 65 years or older, a category in which financial stress is rising because, among other things, of higher taxes and health care costs. In some instances, older couples meet expenses only by reducing their lives to the bare elements, or worse, while simultaneously sitting atop six figures of housing assets. They are well off _ but cash poor. The situation, always a cause of distress among social workers, government officials and others concerned with the elderly, is becoming even more so as large numbers of people enter the upper age categories. Simultaenously, the houses in which they live sometimes continue to rise in value, creating an even more pronounced contrast between cash flow and value tied up in real estate. Repeated attempts to resolve the dilemma have been made over the years, but no private-sector mortgage lender, insurer or other financial institution has marketed a popular solution. Two of the great fears are clearly revealed in surveys: 1. having enough money to live on, and 2. having to move from the Among the possible solutions now available: 1. Sell the house and with the proceeds move into a retirement community. For many people this is a practical solution, but it does n't help those who want to remain right where they are. 2. Sale-leaseback. The house is sold, but the former owners remain where they are. They obtain a guarantee of residency. Money from the sale is invested, and some of it may be used to pay the rent. Drawback: Insecurity resulting from unknowns, chief of which is the ability to make a sufficient return on investments to make monthly rental payments. 3. Home equity line of credit. This enables the owners to draw on home equity to meet unanticipated expenses. The drawback is fear of exhausting the credit line because of living expenses or longevity. 4. Reverse mortgage. Under this plan, monthly sums are withdrawn from the equity and, along with a charge, sent by the lending institution to the owner. In the best of them, the owner receives written assurance of lifetime tenure. Still, there are drawbacks. If the reverse mortgage is for a fixed term, rather than for life, the monthly income is higher, but the assurance of a roof over the head is gone. Lifetime tenure, in effect a reverse annuity mortgage, reduces insecurity but pays relatively little each month. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> estimates that for a 70-year-old borrower, a reverse mortgage on a $ 100,000 home at 10 percent produces $ 654 a month for five years or $ 411 for a 10-year period. However, if the reverse mortgage is for lifetime tenure, the monthly amount drops sharply to $ 278. Actuarial tables suggest strongly that, if possible, it might be wise to delay implementing a reverse mortgage. At age 75, for example, the 5-year note would pay $ 812, the 10-year mortgage $ 510, and the tenure mortgage $ 367. An encouraging development, but largely experimental, is offered through certain lenders by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, which has agreed to insure 2,500 reverse mortgages through September 1991. The issue, however, is much larger than that, and it will become more so as the population ages, the equity piles up and the need to use it becomes pressing. What's needed is the proper product.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tuesday, Dec. 5.</NOTE>
