<FIRST>s i BC-APN--EuropeanCommentary Adv17   12-04 0979</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--European Commentary, Adv 17,0996</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w photos.
ColorFoto subscribers get 3 35mm slides.)</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The changes sweeping Eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are reshaping the Continent. Suddenly the old bipolar equation _ <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> vs. <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> _ has been overturned by the rebirth of an older geographical entity called <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The script is having to be rewritten almost every week. Will <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> become Western democracies? Will the Germanys be united? And if united, will the German colossus once again threaten <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s stability? To try to answer some of these questions, The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> asked five West European commentators to contribute their thoughts. The following overview, the first of five articles, was written by <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON> <PERSON> G.V </PERSON>. Hyde-Price, a research fellow on the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, specializing in <LOCATION> East-West </LOCATION> relations and <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> security.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By ADRIAN G.V. HYDE-PRICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thursday, Nov. 9, the day the East German authorities allowed their citizens to travel freely to the West, marks the simultaneous end of the Cold War and the emergence of the `` German question'' as the decisive issue of European politics. The lifting of the Iron Curtain is cause for celebration and euphoria. At the same time the strategic and political ramifications are enormous, and therefore it is also cause for sober reflection and what the <LOCATION> Dutch </LOCATION> foreign minister has called `` constructive alertness.'' The bipolar structures of the Cold War effectively displaced deep-seated national and ethnic rivalries in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and replaced them with a security system which was, for all its many faults, relatively stable and predictable. One of the crucial features of this security order was the division of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which provided a degree of reassurance to many of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s traditional opponents. Today, however, the old certainties and assumptions of the postwar period are disintegrating under the combined impact of the changes _ associated above all with perestroika in the East, and the 1992 abolition of internal tariff barriers in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. This is nowhere more apparent than in Central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> where, as the Cold War divisions fade away, older patterns of cooperation and conflict are re-emerging. Changes in this sensitive region, however, inevitably open the <PERSON> Pandora </PERSON>'s box of the `` German question,'' which is now the central issue of European politics. The `` German question'' predates the division of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and stems from the difficulty of integrating German power into the European interstate system. <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has traditionally been the fulcrum of the European balance of power, and this is why the recent assertion of `` people power'' in the <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Democratic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> has led to so much discussion about the future of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The reform process in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> will inevitably entail a qualitative change in inner-German relations, and therefore a substantial shift in the balance of power in continental <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The worries are twofold: First, there is the immediate concern about <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s growing economic, political and military weight in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> This has already been felt within the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>, where the West Germans have shown themselves willing and able to assert their national interests, on economic and financial matters as well as over the issue of modernizing Short-range Nuclear Forces. In Eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> economic and political influence has been expanding as the military and political dominance of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has declined. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is now well placed, geographically, economically and culturally, to benefit from the new markets and investment opportunities opened up by the reform movements in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. At the same time, the `` renewal'' movement in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> will inevitably bring the two German states closer together, particularly in the economic sphere, thereby facilitating West German penetration of the rest of <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> is thus set to become both an economic and a political giant in <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> politics. Second, there is the fear that in the long term a reunified, centralized German nation-state -LRB- a `` Fourth Reich'' -RRB- could emerge. Its precondition would be the collapse of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> as a viable political and economic entity. This gives rise to two possible scenarios. First, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> simply expanding to absorb <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, while remaining a member of both the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. This would be unacceptable to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and might unbalance economic and political relations within the Western alliance. The second possibility is that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, faced with a disintegrating East German state, might decide to make the best of a bad deal, and allow <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> to unite and remain a member of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>, provided it became fully denuclearized and all foreign troops withdrew from German soil. This might be acceptable to the Germans, but it would spell the end of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> as an effective military alliance. In order to assuage fears of a reunited and resurgent `` Fourth Reich,'' therefore, it is essential that the West collectively formulate a strategy for managing the changes in <LOCATION> East-Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and in inner-German relations. Above all, a broader European framework must be forged within which the `` German question'' can be successfully managed. This involves recognizing that the self-determination of the German people does not necessarily entail reunification, and that the central issue in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> at the moment is the democratization of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Also, a unified or confederated <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> would only be acceptable to <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s neighbors in the context of a European Community that is both well advanced along the path toward economic and political union, and that is open to new forms of cooperation and association with other democracies in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Within this broader European framework, German power could be diffused upward to the supranational institutions of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and downward to its own regional governments.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
