<FIRST>s i BC-APN--EuropeanCommentary-Ludlow Adv17   12-04 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--European Commentary-Ludlow, Adv 17,0814</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ludlow </PERSON> is director of the Center for European Policy in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, and has written extensively on the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PETER W. LUDLOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Initial comment on the extraordinary events that culminated in the breach of the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall tended to dwell on the damage these developments might inflict on the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. The Federal Republic, it has been suggested, would now be much more interested in reunification than in Western European integration. Every mark spent in <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION> was one less mark available for <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION>. Encouraged perhaps by calculations of this kind, those who were opposed anyway to speeding up the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> integration process by, for example, the convening of an intergovernmental conference on economic and monetary union seized the occasion offered by the events in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and elsewhere to counsel caution. Now was not the time, Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and her allies proclaimed, for the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> to dwell on its own internal problems when so much was happening beyond its frontiers. These early reactions are beginning to appear rather superficial. None of us, it should be stressed, has much idea of how events will develop in the East. They are beyond our control. They also seem to be beyond the control of either government or opposition leaders. The reunification issue is an example. Sober reflection a few days after the Wall came down suggested that speculation about prospects for German unity was largely a Western phenomenon. A few days later, banners in <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION> proclaiming unification as a highly desirable objective complicated the picture yet again. Where the East is going and how quickly remains uncertain. These uncertainties have not, however, prevented the emergence of a fairly widespread consensus among Western European leaders themselves that in the new circumstances the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION>, far from being redundant, is the indispensable cornerstone of any new European system. This consensus, manifested at the highest levels at the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> dinner party for the heads of government and state of the 12 <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> member countries in November rests on various assumptions: _ That the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> is the surest framework within which the Germans themselves can pursue an active policy toward the East and eventually perhaps achieve reunification _ That in a period in which the emphasis in <LOCATION> East-West </LOCATION> relations is bound to rest on economic and non-military matters, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> is best placed to coordinate and channel Western aid and technical assistance _ That in a broader perspective, the Community can and should be seen not only as the most appropriate basis for the European pillar of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> alliance, but also as the indispensable Western pillar in a new European security system in which the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will remain a military superpower regardless of what happens to the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact Against this background, it is now possible to see the Eastern developments as a catalyst of Western integration. In the new circumstances, <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> leaders are almost sure to demonstrate their determination to continue with their own progress toward union: Economic and <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> is the obvious practical initiative, for which highly developed plans already exist. In any case, it is already obvious that the Community will be at the center of a number of high profile efforts to assist the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> directly. These economic and technical means will furthermore be backed up by even more conspicuous political initiatives involving, as President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> implied after the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> summit, visits to <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> at the highest level. Finally, the acceleration of events and the obvious intention of <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> leaders to play an active role can only strengthen those elements in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration who already see the Community collectively as the ideal long-term partner with whom to discuss not only economic issues, but also political and security questions. For those committed to the further development of <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> union, these prospects can only be highly gratifying. There are, however, serious dangers that the West European themselves should be the first to recognize and deal with: _ A stronger <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> organized through the European Community can and should be a major asset to the Western Alliance It is not, however, as currently organized, in any practical sense linked to the alliance machinery. _ More important, a stronger <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> that is a magnet to the East almost certainly will be seen in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> as a potential threat, ready in the worst case to gobble up dissident members of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact However unfounded these fears may be, the Community should take active steps to reassure the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and to cooperate with it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
