<FIRST>s i BC-APN--EuropeanCommentary-Bogdanor Adv17   12-04 0763</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--European Commentary-Bogdanor, Adv 17,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogdanor </PERSON> is a Fellow of <ORGANIZATION> Brasenose </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>, and a lecturer in politics at <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. He writes extensively on constitutional and European Community affairs.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By VERNON BOGDANOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is in, but not of, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. She did not share the psychology of the original six who founded the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> in 1958 _ <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Federal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, all of whom suffered from fascism and enemy occupation For them, World War II showed that the nation-state had to be overcome through the creation of supranational institutions. For <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the war meant the triumph of the nation-state _ her finest hour. Not feeling ashamed of her past, she felt assured of her future as a global superpower, the center of a worldwide empire rather than a middle-ranking European country. She has always known that sooner or later she will have to put aside her ambivalence and decide whether to join the Continent or stand aside. The cataclysmic changes in central and eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> ought to bring this moment of truth closer. Although the late French president <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON> did his best to keep <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> out of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, the British approach to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> has always been Gaullist. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> favors a <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> of cooperating but sovereign independent nations, rather than any pooling of sovereignty. Entering the Community in 1973, she thought she was joining merely a customs union rather than a dynamic organization whose purpose was European union. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> has given forceful expression to this conception of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Superficially, the changes in central and eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> make the British government's case for a loosely organized Community more plausible. For if Central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> is being unraveled, what is the sense in continuing with the creation of a closed Community in the West? Instead, so the British argument goes, new forms of association need to be created that can bridge the ever-narrowing ideological gap between West and East. It would be parochial to concentrate on the machinery of integration _ exchange rates, monetary union and the like _ when the solid scaffolding of the <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> we knew is disintegrating before our eyes This conception, in the view of most of the other governments in the Community, ignores the vastly increased danger of instability in Central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The withdrawal of Communism is likely to bring to the surface all kinds of national conflicts, submerged since the war through the might of the Soviet Empire. In particular, a reunited <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which now looks a distinct possibility, could threaten the balance of power in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. It especially frightens the Poles, whose frontiers, in the absence of a peace treaty, have still to be finally agreed; and the French, invaded three times by <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in the past 120 years. The French, therefore, are in the vanguard of those arguing that German reunification can only be safely attempted if <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> becomes fully integrated into the European Community. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> does not share this fear of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Less traumatized by World War II, she was more willing to forgive and forget. Less scarred by history, she finds it difficult to imagine a reunited <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> as anything other than benign. Traditionally, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s role in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> has been to stand apart, preserving the balance of power against the attempt of any single power to dominate the Continent That remains the instinct of many leading British Conservatives. The opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has recently taken a distinctly more pro-European stance. Yet this transformation of attitudes _ it was the Conservatives who took <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> into the Community, while as recently as 1983 Labor was promising withdrawal from it _ owes as much to hostility toward Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> as to genuine European conviction. There are signs that attitudes are changing. Survey evidence earlier this year suggested that 55 percent of the British electorate regarded the Community as a `` good thing,'' the highest figure since <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> joined. The Euro-elections, which were catastrophic for Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, showed that there is no longer a strong anti-European constituency in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. It remains to be seen whether the convulsions in Central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> will finally convince the public that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is essentially a European power. Eventually, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> will have to make a decision of principle _ whether she wishes to be part of the new political entity being created in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, or remain an offshore island devoid of both power and influence.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
