<FIRST>s a BC-APN--JapaneseSchool Adv17   12-04 0906</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Japanese School, Adv 17,0932</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.)</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 A new high school soon to open in the suburbs of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> reflects the growing Japanese presence in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The aim of the school is to prepare Japanese children for college back in their home country. There are some decided differences in the way students are drilled in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 East will meet West on the campus of <ORGANIZATION> Keio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, an experimental academy that will teach the children of Japanese executives posted in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The school, on the grounds of <ORGANIZATION> Manhattanville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in this suburb of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, is scheduled to open in September 1990. Construction of a classroom and administrative building, a gymnasium, cafeteria and dormitories began in the fall. <ORGANIZATION> Keio </ORGANIZATION> was conceived as a way to attract Japanese businesses to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state. But it is now seen as an important educational effort in its own right _ an experiment in bilingual, bicultural education that could help expand the horizons of education in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` The school is a bellwether for the state, if not the country,'' says <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, the regional representative on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regents </ORGANIZATION>, the state's educational policy board. `` It could become an instant model.'' The catalyst for the creation of the school was concern about the education of the children of the growing number of Japanese businessmen who work in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. An estimated 20,000 to 30,000 live in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> alone, the most in any area of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Yasumitsu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nihei </PERSON>, who will be principal of the new school, says the average stay of the Japanese businessman once was about five years. But now they're staying longer, and the needs of their college-bound children are more important. Most Japanese children want to attend a university in their homeland `` to be mainstream in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' says <PERSON> Nihei </PERSON>. In many cases, workers stay with a single company all their lives, and to get into that company they must get into the right school, he says. But to get into the university, students must pass an examination. All of their previous education from the second grade on is geared toward drilling them with the facts necessary to pass that test. They attend school eight hours a day, 5 -LCB- days a week, 240 days a year. By comparison, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> students attend six hours a day, five days a week for about 180 days a year. And American schools concentrate less on the rote memorization that is commonplace at Japanese schools. There is an elementary school based on the Japanese system in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. But until recently, high school students often were sent home to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Meiji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gakuin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> plans to open a traditional Japanese high school in <LOCATION> Sweetwater </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, where 70 Japanese-owned companies, including <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> and <PERSON> Matsushita </PERSON>, have operations. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynam </PERSON>, a spokesman for Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, said <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> had seized on the establishment of a school to help Japanese businessmen already here and attract more. <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s prestigious <ORGANIZATION> Keio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> was consulted. <PERSON> Matilda </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, the governor's wife, even visited the university during negotiations. They settled on <LOCATION> Manhattanville </LOCATION> as the site of the new school because it was close to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and because <LOCATION> Manhattanville </LOCATION> has a sister school in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the University of the Sacred Heart. Half the faculty in the new school will be <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and the curriculum will cull the best from the American school system, particularly an emphasis on writing, which is more American than Japanese. The curriculum will meet graduation requirements of both <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and an outstanding student at the school would be assured entry into <ORGANIZATION> Keio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> without the dreaded exam. While it is expected that Japanese students will make up most of the student body, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> students will not be excluded. Entrance into the school will be based on an exam, grades, bilingual ability demonstrated in written essays, letters of recommendation and extracurricular activities. The school will operate on two semesters and will accommodate both the Japanese school year, which runs April to March, and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> school year. Tuition is projected at $ 12,000 a year, room and board at $ 4,000. Manhattanville President <PERSON> Marcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Savage </PERSON> said students from her school will student-teach at the school or work in labs there. Dr. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Valenti </PERSON>, superintendent of <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> schools, is also looking forward to a partnership with his Asian neighbor. In his district, 6.7 percent of the district's 2,166 students are Asian, mostly Japanese, but only 24 students in the <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> high school system are <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> currently offers a bilingual program for Japanese students at its <ORGANIZATION> Parsons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's an opportunity for us to share programs, for both of us to learn,'' <PERSON> Valenti </PERSON> says. `` Some of our Japanese students prefer the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> experience and want to go to an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>.'' <ORGANIZATION> Keio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, which is investing $ 40 million in the school, including $ 9.5 million to buy 27 acres of the <LOCATION> Manhattanville </LOCATION> campus, feels the experiment could pay dividends at home. `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is in an age of internationalization,'' says <PERSON> Nihei </PERSON>, who hopes the school's success will lead to similar programs elsewhere in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
