<FIRST>s a BC-APN--PrisonPerformer Adv17   12-04 0906</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Prison Performer, Adv 17,0933</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.)</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 It's hard to imagine devoting one's life to penetrating the forbidding walls of a prison and trying to reach the hearts of convicts, but this <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> woman does it and her message is: `` I am me and I am good cuz God do n't make junk.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FREESOIL, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` People think these boys are just throwaways, that they're getting what they deserve. I think the public needs to know that God is behind prison walls.'' That's the feeling of <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>, who with accordion and Bible in hand walks through prison doors each Sunday to try to inspire even the most hardened inmates. In a drafty room once used as a barracks for prisoners, the spry grandmother of two stands before about 100 uniformed inmates at Camp Sauble, the state's only boot-camp-style corrections facility. `` My heart is behind the prison doors with you,'' she says to the men, most of them repeat offenders under age 25. After having former drill instructors bark orders in their face all week, many of the young men crack a smile for the first time since the previous Sunday. `` When I first came here, I did n't want to go to church services,'' says inmate <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, 19, of <LOCATION> Dowagiac </LOCATION>, who was sent to Camp Sauble on a breaking and entering conviction. `` But when you see her, it brings your spirits up and makes you feel better for the rest of the week.'' `` I'm glad my Mom made me take accordion lessons, because it's opened quite a lot of prison doors,'' <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> says with a chuckle One of her hymns she wrote herself, and it sums up her message: `` I am me and I am good cuz God do n't make junk.'' <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> began her mostly musical church services at Camp Sauble in 1984, two years after she took early retirement from a 17-year career as a case worker with the <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. When she's not at Camp Sauble on Sunday, <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> can be found at other <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> prisons. She plays monthly at the minimum-security prison at <LOCATION> Cassidy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> near <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON> and at the <ORGANIZATION> Kinross </ORGANIZATION> medium-security facility in the <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. She's also a regular visitor at several other prisons, including camps Cusino and Ojibway in the <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> and camps <PERSON> Pellston </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pugsley </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Lower </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. Attendance at <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' services usually runs a remarkable 98 percent, compared with about 10 percent at most prisons across the state, officials say. Those who choose not to attend must stay in their cells for `` quiet time.'' Most weeks, the only inmates not in attendance are those who are banned as punishment, guards say. Prison officials say <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' services seem to touch many of the inmates. `` They really put their heart and soul in the services,'' says Officer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>. `` That Sunday service gives them the drive to complete the week.'' Accompanied by her brother on the banjo, <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' songs are upbeat, an inspiration to the offenders who have been given 90 days to change their ways. If they fail, they are sent to a conventional prison, usually with a much longer sentence. There are the traditional hymns, such as `` Amazing Grace,'' and within a few minutes, nearly every one of the men is clapping and singing along in thunderous voices as <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> belts out the tunes on her accordion. After every song they roar their approval. A brief Christian service follows. Inmates read along with their donated Bibles and bow their shaved heads in prayer. A guard patrols the room. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' musical prowess also includes the piano, organ and guitar. In her 20s, she sang in an all-girl dance band in <LOCATION> Lansing </LOCATION>, where she grew up. Besides her commitment to people behind bars, <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> deviates from the stereotypical grandmother image in other ways. She recently sold her motorcycle, which had earned her the nickname `` Motorcycle Mama'' among friends. `` I never had the time to ride it,'' she says. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' first prison performance came when a fellow male member at her Assembly of God church who had been playing guitar for inmates at Camp Sauble _ then a regular minimum-security prison _ asked her to fill in one Sunday. `` It became an addiction,'' she says. She also began teaching Bible class at the prison every Tuesday. It was at those Bible classes, which eventually grew to 40 students, that she cultivated friendships with about 20 prisoners. When they were transferred to other state prisons in early 1988 to make room for the boot camp, <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> began corresponding and visiting them all over the state. `` They became like family,'' she says. `` Some of them have no visitors but me.'' Many have sent her paintings and small, prison-made artifacts. Only about five of the original 20 men remain behind bars, and many stopped corresponding upon their release, <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> says. `` That does n't bother me. I had a part of their life while they were here, but they want to put their past behind them when they get out.'' <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> does n't get any money for her prison work, but emphasizes that she does n't do it for recognition, monetary or otherwise. `` Money would never equal what I get back from these boys,'' she says.
</TEXT>
