<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> had doubts about acting in `` The Merchant of <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>'' until she learned that her co-star was <PERSON> Dustin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>. `` When I knew who was playing Shylock, I became rather keen to do it, unsurprisingly,'' says the 39-year-old English actress, fresh from a sellout <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> run as <LOCATION> Portia </LOCATION> to <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>'s Jewish moneylender in <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>'s dark comedy of caskets, the law and revenge. The production, directed by Sir <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, marked <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>'s British and Shakespearean stage debut and packed <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> Theater for 18 weeks The play is now on view at Broadway's 46th St. Theater for a limited engagement through Feb. 24. It gives Americans the opportunity to see a two-time Oscar-winner tackle <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON> in a performance which, <PERSON> James </PERSON> says, changed nightly in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. `` To do the trial scene, I used to walk on every day not knowing what was going to happen,'' she says, referring to <PERSON> Portia </PERSON>'s fourth-act encounter with Shylock, the beleaguered and vengeful moneylender who meets his match in the heiress, <LOCATION> Portia </LOCATION> `` When <PERSON> Dustin </PERSON> was truthful, even if he took choices that were wrong, he was always brilliant _ so riveting and unexpected,'' she says. `` I felt very protective of him ... The whole company as a company was so proud to be working with him. He was so generous, spiritually and literally. He would n't have his name over the title, and insisted on me having the last curtain call.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> used a six-week break before <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> rehearsals to regather her artistic strength. `` We do n't ask opera singers to do <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> eight times a week, and honestly, I am exhausted,'' she says. `` <LOCATION> Portia </LOCATION> is a very big, quite tiring part.'' The blonde, big-boned actress is best-known to American audiences for her portrayal of <LOCATION> Mirabehn </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mahatma </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s acolyte in the Oscar-winning movie about the Indian leader's life, and as <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Layton </PERSON>, the India-born daughter of a British colonel, in the 1984 TV miniseries `` The Jewel in the Crown.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON>' first experience in `` Merchant'' came while playing <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON>, Shylock's daughter, in a provincial production 10 years ago in the English midlands city of Coventry. Then, she recalls, <PERSON> Portia </PERSON> struck her as `` a bit of a know-all.'' Now, she finds her `` a miraculous character,'' and attributes her shift in perceptions to <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s direction. `` With <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>, he is the master, he can tell you how to do it,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> says. `` If I was going to see <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON> for the first time, I would choose a Peter Hall production. He may not go for innovation, but he does the play.'' <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> says he admired <PERSON> James </PERSON>'s `` natural musicality and sense of rhythm ... She ` sa very intelligent, feisty actress <PERSON> James </PERSON> says the director encouraged her to explore the contradictions of a character who can seem dismissive and even racist one minute, ripe with `` the quality of mercy'' _ in <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>'s celebrated phrase _ the next. `` It's tempting to iron those contradictions out so that characters become one-dimensional in order to become recognizable,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> says. `` As actors we always want to be liked; it's much braver to dare to be disliked.'' She says <PERSON> Portia </PERSON>'s complexities `` are part of her interest.'' `` People say, ` How can someone be as nice and as nasty as <PERSON> Portia </PERSON>?' But we're very often like that,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> says. `` It's much too simple to say <PERSON> Portia </PERSON>'s any one thing, because she's all of them. `` It's important to win an audience around through convincing them of the truth of the character.'' `` Merchant'' reunited <PERSON> James </PERSON> with <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, who directed her as <PERSON> Imogen </PERSON> in <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>'s `` Cymbeline'' last year at the National Theater. She replaced <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> just three weeks before the first preview of <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>'s sprawling, rarely performed late romance. `` It was wonderful doing ` Cymbeline' knowing people did n't know it at all,'' she says. `` Those who came discovered the play.'' She also starred in <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s first film in 15 years, `` She's Been Away,'' as the self-destructive banker's wife. She and co-star <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashcroft </PERSON> shared the best actress prize at the <ORGANIZATION> Venice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> in September. `` I had worked with <PERSON> Peter </PERSON>; <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> had worked with <PERSON> Peter </PERSON>; I had worked with <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> says. `` A lot of things about it made sense.'' She and the legendary <PERSON> Ashcroft </PERSON>, now 81, co-starred in `` The Jewel in the Crown,'' about the end of British rule in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. And the afterglow lingers on: `` I get letters still from <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. They have ` Jewel in the Crown' evenings, watching it on video, eating curries and wearing saris.'' Her training, typical of many English performers, was in the theater. She studied at the <ORGANIZATION> Drama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and did a stint as a dresser with the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shakespeare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, which was then presenting <PERSON> Ashcroft </PERSON> in <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Albee </PERSON>'s `` A Delicate Balance.'' Years in regional repertory theaters led to the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> `` fringe'' and on to the commercial <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> End </LOCATION>, where she starred opposite <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> in `` When I Was a Girl, I Used To Scream and Shout.'' Her first major screen part was in `` Gandhi.'' Earlier this year, she appeared with <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldblum </PERSON> in a new film comedy, `` The Tall Guy.'' Neither that film nor `` She's Been Away'' has yet been released in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> James </PERSON> will be seen later this year on-screen in `` The Wolves of <LOCATION> Willoughby </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chase </LOCATION>,'' starring <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Beacham </PERSON> from `` The Colbys'' and `` Dynasty.'' Next year, she and <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Kingsley </PERSON>, her `` Gandhi'' co-star, re-team for a two-character play, <PERSON> Lanford </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s `` A Betrothal,'' which they first performed above a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> pub three years ago. <PERSON> James </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Berkshire </LOCATION>, west of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one of three children and the daughter of a cardiologist. The product of `` a typical middle-class family,'' she says she became an actress more or less against the wishes of her parents. `` But if the spirits want you to be something, you be it,'' she says.
