<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: `She-Devil'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 `` She-Devil'' is a revenge movie without Sly, <PERSON> Clint </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION> or <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON>. This time it's <PERSON> Roseanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> who shows those vengeful gents the kind of hell that a scorned woman can administer. <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> is the dull, slovenly, accident-prone wife of <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Begley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, an ambitious <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> accountant with amazing tolerance for her many failings. They include running their suburban home like a city slum and mismanaging their two overbearing children. When the couple attends a gallery opening in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, he falls into the clutches of a man-hungry, self-adoring writer of romance novels, <PERSON> Meryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Streep </PERSON>. Weary of her live-in gigolo, she decides to give the accountant her business and her love. <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> slowly realizes her husband has been led astray. She boils with Mephistophelean wrath, vowing to rob him of everything he holds dear: his family life, his career, his new love, his freedom. Her methods are as far-fetched as they are hilarious. Full-out farce such as `` She-Devil'' requires a feathery directorial touch and the most delicate of playing. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Seidelman </PERSON>'s direction is on target most of the way, maintaining a whirlwind pace that forestalls suspension of belief. The script by <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Strugatz </PERSON> is cleverly constructed, though some of the comedy is misdirected -LRB- example: the spoofing of senility in a retirement sanitarium -RRB-. The movie is based on the novel, `` The Life and Loves of a She-Devil,'' by <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> <PERSON> Weldon </PERSON>. Set in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the novel was made into a critically accl