<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lute </PERSON> <PERSON> Suites </PERSON>, by <PERSON> Johann </PERSON> <PERSON> Sebastian </PERSON> <PERSON> Bach </PERSON> -LRB- <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> -RRB- _ <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, guitar Compact disc enemies now have some new ammunition. This recording not only reproduces <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>'s sound in crystal, it also captures to a distracting degree the clicking, zinging sounds of the mechanics of playing his instrument. Aside from the the suites, this two-disc set offers transcriptions of assorted <PERSON> Bach </PERSON> works for violin and harpsichord, confined to a second disc timed at a pitiful 44.59. <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> is also a little ungenerous musically. His techically fine playing sounds not especially sensitive, on this recording at least. Lines are not well shaped and do n't always emerge independently, and the phrasing sometimes sounds rushed. _ By <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakin </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Deaf, Dumb, and Blonde'' -LRB- Sire -RRB- _ <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> `` </PERSON> <PERSON> Deaf </PERSON>, Dumb and Blonde'' is <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>'s third solo effort since the breakup of the punk bastion <PERSON> Blondie </PERSON>. Unfortunately, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> has locked into today's pop format and the album lacks her snarling early 1980s cleverness. Two of the tracks, including the lead single, `` I Want That Man,'' were written by <PERSON> Allanah </PERSON> <PERSON> Currie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Thompson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Twins </ORGANIZATION>, and their influence permeates most of the record in the form of snappy beats and almost mundane lyrics. On the few songs <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> wrote with ex-boyfriend <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Stein </PERSON>, the dark, brooding punk attitudes return. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>'s self-confident lyrics and <PERSON> Stein </PERSON>'s menacing guitar combine on several notable tracks. `` Lovelight,'' a duet with <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Astbury </PERSON> of The Cult, mixes paradoxical imagery with Indian rhythms to tell of love in a cryptic, mystical setting. `` Calmarie,'' which <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> sings partly in Spanish, is a lovely showcase for the higher register of her voice. `` Brite Side'' produces a more tender side. She is confident, but not arrogant; loving, but not worshiping. You have to wait for most of the record for a real knockout. That comes with the last track, the gorgeously arranged `` End of the Run.'' It is a partly spoken song-poem that tells of <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>'s beginnings: `` when a torn T-shirt made it all dangerous. In it, she says she `` does n't like flashbacks in movies ... I like the story to proceed.'' <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>'s story has proceeded, but into what's threatening to look like pop dribble. She's called her new music `` simpler and more aggressive.'' Simpler, yes. More agressive, no. By <PERSON> Kira </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Billik </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
