<HEAD>On Show: Gallery and Museum Exhibits and Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> has put together a major traveling exhibit of more than 150 works by 49 black artists of the 20th century. `` Black Art-Ancestral Legacy: The African Impulse in African-American Art'' opened Dec. 3 and will run through Feb. 25 before moving on to the High Musuem in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>. The importance of African cultural traditions to the creativity of black artists in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> is the focus of the exhibit. `` Unlike the American and European modernists who borrowed the forms of ` primitive' African sculpture early in the 20th century, African-American artists tapped into the wellspring of their ancestral art to produce a new synthesis of the African and the American,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bretell </PERSON>, director of the museum. `` When an African-American artist makes use of snake imagery, of woven patterns, or of repetititve images derived from dance, he is not merely ` borrowing' forms, but making a powerful statement about cultural continuity.'' The exhibit features works by such artists as <PERSON> Richmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Barthe </PERSON>, <PERSON> Xenobia </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sargent </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Love </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Biggers </PERSON> and <PERSON> Derek </