<HEAD>Star Watch: Chase Takes Charge of His Career</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1 of Dec. 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After a dozen years in movies, <LOCATION> Chevy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chase </LOCATION> can still take a tumble to get a laugh, but he is learning not to risk career falls because of bad advice. The lesson has n't come easily for the tall, preppie-looking comedian. After creating a falling-down sensation on `` Saturday Night Live,'' he made an impressive film debut in `` Foul Play'' and followed with big-money hits such as `` Caddyshack,'' `` National Lampoon's Vacation'' and `` Fletch.'' But along the way he encountered films that might have submerged a less durable performer: `` Under the Rainbow,'' `` Oh! Heavenly Dog,'' `` Modern Problems,'' `` The Deal of the Century.'' Despite such disasters, Chase has survived and reportedly draws $ 5 million per movie. His latest is `` National Lampoon's Christmas Vacation,'' which reunites him with `` Vacation'' buddies <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Angelo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Quaid </PERSON>. Chase has finally reached a point where he decided he had to take charge of his own career. `` I do n't think there's a star around who does n't feel that way,'' he reflected. `` The problem with that is that it can become too egotistical, too warped by your own lack of introspection and perspective. `` The world is different -LRB- when you're a star -RRB-. It behaves differently towards you. You're no longer just like anybody else around you. You have to remember there's such a thing as compromise and collaboration. On top of that, of all the arts that I'm familiar with, film is the most collaborative `` I was reading an article about <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedkin </PERSON> -LRB- ` The Exorcist' -RRB- the other day. He said, ` I do n't consider myself any more or less important than a crew member.' We all know that's not true of <PERSON> Bill </PERSON>. We know that he would like to think that and that he means it. The fact is that his ego takes over, and he gets crazy. He's also a brilliant director.'' <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> cited last year's `` Fletch Lives'' as evidence of why he needs to make his own decisions. `` Quite frankly, I had a lot of trepidation about the ` Fletch' sequel It was in the middle of the writers' strike. I was the only one who kept saying, ` No, it's not gon na work, it's not happening.' ... Everybody at Universal: ` It's going to be great, do n't worry.' Me: ` No, it's not working. `` I hate that. And yet I go along with it. It ends up with me putting on a lot of funny faces and trying to mug my way through a picture. It worked for what it was. But I did n't think it was a good picture. Then I have to go out on a junket and promote it, the whole time feeling bad about it.'' Chase does n't feel that way about `` Christmas Vacation.'' `` I think it can stand on its own as a picture,'' he said. `` It's got a lot of the richness of the first ` Vacation,' if you can call that stuff rich. It's written by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, as the first one was. ... It's directed by a very talented young director named <PERSON> Jeremiah </PERSON> <PERSON> Chechik </PERSON>, who's got a great eye and a lot of warmth. `` And it's very physical, more physical in the <PERSON> Buster </PERSON> <PERSON> Keaton </PERSON> tradition than I've ever done before. I love that stuff.'' <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> said he participated in all the production decisions, from the first meeting with executives from <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> until the final print. If he is so gung-ho on control, why does n't he direct his own films, like <PERSON> Clint </PERSON> <PERSON> Eastwood </PERSON> and <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>? `` Clint's children are grown up; <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> does n't have any,'' he pointed out. `` I'm not prepared to take myself away from my family for the amount of time -LRB- needed to direct a film -RRB-. I try to be as much a part of the directing process as I can, without being away from my family. `` It's hard enough to be the star and see your family during that three-month production period. If you direct a movie, you're looking at a year This is a very important, precious period in my kids' lives,'' he said. Chase has three children. `` They are from one to six years old, and a five-year-old. They need the accessibility of their dad, as well as their mom. The fact is, I need it, too.'' His resolve may stem from his own childhood: `` I came from a divorced family, and that was very tough. I think it has affected me all my life. I think it affects anyone whose parents are divorced. I do n't like it, I do n't like to see it happen. It's hard on the kids.'' He was born into a wealthy <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> family on Oct. 8, 1943, and named <PERSON> Cornelius </PERSON> <PERSON> Crane </PERSON> <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> -LRB- his grandmother provided the <LOCATION> Chevy </LOCATION>, perhaps after the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> suburb -RRB-. An expensive education provided a bachelor of arts degree in English and a determination to perform. After writing for Mad magazine and the <ORGANIZATION> Smothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION>, he fell in with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lampoon </ORGANIZATION> people and ended up in the first cast of `` Saturday Night Live.''
</TEXT>
