<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Canadian Band Makes Movie Debut</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5 of Dec. 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Canadian rockers Blue Rodeo are used to stealing shows on their own, but in their recent movie debut they played backup band to country and western singer Meryl Streep. Meryl Streep? That's right. And, according to <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rodeo </ORGANIZATION> vocalist <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Keelor </PERSON>, the band has the Academy Award-winning actress' chauffeur to thank for the gig. Platinum-selling artists in their native <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, the five members of Blue Rodeo hope their cameo with Streep in next year's release of `` Postcards From the Edge'' and their new album, `` Diamond Mine,'' will propel them to similar status in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` She's very good,'' group member <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuddy </PERSON> said of Streep's performance on `` Checking Out of the Heartbreak Hotel. `` She can sing very well. She's probably kind of a boundless entertainer.'' Filmmaker <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> wanted a group that sounded like an early version of The Band. Blue Rodeo, who performed with former Band members <PERSON> Robbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Danko </PERSON> and <PERSON> Garth </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> on the Canadian Juno Awards show earlier this year, was one of five bands asked to submit tapes. Streep was listening to the tapes while being driven into <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> when her chauffeur raved about Blue Rodeo's 1987 debut, `` Outskirts,'' <PERSON> Keelor </PERSON> said. Soon after, <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rodeo </ORGANIZATION> auditioned and won the movie role. `` It was a very normal kind of experience,'' said <PERSON> Cuddy </PERSON>, whose band rehearsed <PERSON> Patsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cline </PERSON> songs with Streep before shooting the scene. `` I'm sure that's not the typical Hollywood experience. This was one of the first times we've stayed in separate rooms.'' Blue Rodeo traces its roots to the late 1970s, when <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> natives <PERSON> Keelor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cuddy </PERSON> rather violently crossed paths for the first time. <PERSON> Cuddy </PERSON> was a football linebacker who slammed quarterback <PERSON> Keelor </PERSON> to the ground in a scrimmage. Nevertheless, they soon became friends and began writing songs together. Keelor and <PERSON> Cuddy </PERSON> moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> in the early'80s looking to succeed with Fly to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, a rock band they admit now was unfocused. Fly to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> shared rehearsal space with <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> friends who formed the <ORGANIZATION> Cowboy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junkies </ORGANIZATION>. Trying to make it in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> proved unsatisfying, typified by the disappointment the pair heard from musicians who responded to their newspaper ad and found they would n't be flown to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> for auditions, <PERSON> Cuddy </PERSON> said. They moved back to <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> in 1984 and ditched Fly to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. They formed Blue Rodeo, adding acoustic guitars to their collection and aiming for a country-rock hybrid inspired by the <ORGANIZATION> Everly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> and the Beatles. `` It was the music to do,'' said the 33-year-old <PERSON> Cuddy </PERSON>. `` It gives an artist a certain longevity, a certain respectability that is not always evident in pop music. To just chase pop music and chase an audience that's half your age is a little ridiculous... It's especially embarrassing if you get rejected by 11-year-olds.'' Despite a twang in their sound, Blue Rodeo does n't feel comfortable in the world of country music. And, frankly, country music probably would n't feel comfortable with a band whose keyboard player occasionally solos by standing barefoot on his organ. `` I like the harmonies and I like the mournfulness of it,'' <PERSON> Cuddy </PERSON> said of country music. `` I've always liked the details in the lyrics, the focus on small details, but I've never wanted to be a full-fledged member of country music. It's just not something that appeals to me. I think we're rock musicians borrowing from country.'' Like a certain famed British songwriting duo they admired, <PERSON> Cuddy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Keelor </PERSON>'s styles are often a contrast between the sinister and the sweet. <PERSON> Cuddy </PERSON>'s smooth voice highlights country ballads like `` Try,'' which won a Juno Award for Canadian song of the year in 1988, and new songs `` Now and Forever'' and `` House of Dreams.'' <PERSON> Keelor </PERSON>'s vocal phrasing is a dead ringer for early <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Costello </PERSON> on `` The Ballad of the Dime Store Greaser and the Blonde <PERSON> Mona </PERSON> <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'' and, with keyboard player <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiseman </PERSON>, he creates an eerie, Doors-like sound on the new album's title cut. The contrast can be jarring on record but makes more sense onstage when the pair harmonize, said <PERSON> Keelor </PERSON>, 35. `` It's certainly an advantage in that you can cover a lot of ground in songwriting,'' <PERSON> Cuddy </PERSON> said. `` We can approach things from a couple of different ways. And just from a physical standpoint, it's nice not to have to sing all night.'' Blue Rodeo's sound, for lack of a more appropriate word, has been described as quintessentially American. They're not afraid to sing about their southern neighbors; `` God and Country'' is about <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>. `` There's also a sort of Canadian tradition in the band, like <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, of writing a lot about <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Keelor </PERSON> said. `` But it's with a different perspective, it's like with a distance. `` The modern world has a fascination with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But for us, it's even more tangible. We speak the language. We can cross the borders and work down here as legal aliens. I did that for years.'' But <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rodeo </ORGANIZATION>'s own success points out differences between the two countries. In <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, `` Outskirts'' was the country's equivalent of a double-platinum album -LRB- more than 200,000 sold -RRB- and the band plays in concert halls. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, they're critical favorites but are largely unknown. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, a double-platinum LP would mean that more than 2 million copies were sold. At a recent Blue Rodeo performance in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, dozens of Canadians packed the Lone Star Roadhouse. A cardboard cutout of a Canadian Mountie hung over the stage. Such questions as `` what province are you from?'' replaced typical <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> small talk. `` The success we have in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> is pretty good for us,'' <PERSON> Keelor </PERSON> said. `` We'd like to do the same thing here. A large part of it is just to keep playing and have people see us. We're fairly confident that when people see us, they'll like it. It's a good show.''
