<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Year of Milestones for Bill Monroe</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NS2 of Dec. 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's been a year of milestones for <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>, `` the father of bluegrass music.'' In October, the stately 78-year-old celebrated his 50th anniversary on the Grand Ole Opry, the live country music show he helped transform into an American institution. In February, he won a Grammy Award in a newly added category: best bluegrass recording. And he ended the decade the way he began it: chatting with the president at the White House. In 1980, he played his beloved mandolin on the White House lawn for President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>. This November, he was invited to 1600 <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> to meet President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. When the celebrations and awards and <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> visits subside, <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> can sit at his office desk and read a sticker pasted on the wall: `` Bluegrass: finger picking good.'' This music, developed by <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> in the 1930s, has been mighty good indeed to this legendary performer. Millions have heard him on the Grand Ole Opry or in live performances. He's entertained in every state and in several foreign countries. He's sold more than 50 million records. In 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> adopted a resolution honoring him for `` many contributions to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> culture and music.'' He says he's lasted so long because he took care of himself and enjoyed singing and playing. `` I've always liked work and I've been stout,'' he said in an interview. `` I've taken care of myself and never did smoke or drink. Work is something I've always liked to do. I like to do something every day. `` I love to play music and hear it. I love to put the sounds and notes in there that I want to hear. I want to do the best I can for my friends and fans sitting out there in the audience.'' <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>, a descendant of the fifth president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, is best known for his songs `` Blue Moon of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>,'' `` Uncle Pen'' and `` Mule Skinner Blues.'' `` Blue Moon of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>,'' which he wrote in 1946, was recorded some 10 years later by <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Presley </PERSON>. `` I knew he was coming with another style of music,'' <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> recalled. `` One Saturday night, they had him on the Grand Ole Opry. He came around to me and apologized for singing the way he did.'' `` I told him if it gave him a good start with his music and everything, I was for him 100 percent. So our friendship stood good all the way.'' Born near <LOCATION> Rosine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> was the youngest of eight children and was orphaned by age 11. He was raised by an uncle who was an excellent fiddler and mandolinist. By age 12, <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> was playing music at dances with his uncle and perfecting his tenor voice that was to enthrall millions for years to come. Down through the years, he taught bluegrass music _ the string music of guitars, banjos, fiddles and mandolins _ to disciples such as <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> Flatt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Scruggs </PERSON>, who played in his band, the Bluegrass Boys. <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> has recorded for <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> Records for nearly 40 years, a rarity in the music industry where performers often change labels every few years. `` They've been a big help to me and we work together good,'' he said. His most recent album is `` <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> and the Bluegrass Boys Live at the Opry.'' He still performs 100 times a year at bluegrass festivals, country music shows and the like. In his office is a lined white sheet of paper with a place on each line for the date and the city he's booked in. Even after more than 50 years on the road, he still finds travel inspirational. `` I like to see the hills and mountains and valleys and how they take care of the land and everything,'' <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> said. He's been blessed with good health and a steely determination to keep his music alive. When he was diagnosed with colon cancer in the early 1980s, he fought it with the spirit he shows as his nimble fingers dance along the neck of his mandolin. `` The doctor said I whipped the cancer out,'' <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
