<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Idaho Centennial,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Travel: Idaho Centennial ^By DAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Visitors who visit <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> during its 1990 Centennial have a unique opportunity to experience the theme that runs through the state's history like a vein of gold _ man's love affair with the land. The Gem State's 100th birthday party will feature a gamut of `` Wild West'' celebrations in virtually every town and county. And there is the added reward of traveling through eye-catching <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> became the 43rd state on July 3, 1890. Settlers traveled to <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> for its resources: gold and silver, endless stands of timber, the rich volcanic soil. `` People who came here were looking for something to exploit, but not in the bad sense,'' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centennial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> who spent 17 years as director of the <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. One of the most involved projects in the celebration is the creation of a Centennial Park. State officials insisted that monument reflect industry's role in opening up the wild territory to civilization. Mining attracted the first major influx of settlers, so it was natural to locate the park around the old gold rush towns of <LOCATION> Custer </LOCATION> and Bonanza in central <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. Those rustic ghost towns are a short jaunt off <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> 75, nestled in the pines along the <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fork </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> Salmon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Ore wagons rattled along the Motorway toll road to the ranching community of <PERSON> Challis </PERSON>, where the park's interpretive center will be built. `` We had two Oregon Trail parks, but we did n't have any park for mining, which brought them here in the first place,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said. `` The Oregon Trail people passed through <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, but did n't think they could farm here.'' Within two hour's drive from the Centennial Park are the granite crags of the <LOCATION> Sawtooth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, the champagne whitewater of the Middle and Main forks of the Salmon, or the world-class ski slopes of <LOCATION> Sun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. The resort retains the 1940s aura that attracted the world's elite: <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> and <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Gable </PERSON>, to name a few. The Silver Valley in the <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Panhandle </LOCATION> historically has ranked as one of the top 10 mining districts in the world. Travelers intending to put in a busy day can visit the <ORGANIZATION> Coeur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> d'Alene </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Wallace </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>'s oldest standing building in the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cataldo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> built in 1853, or the lakeside resort community of <ORGANIZATION> Coeur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> d'Alene </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Cataldo </PERSON> was built by Jesuit priests and local Indians using wooden pegs instead of nails. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s longest gondola will soon stretch from the town of <LOCATION> Kellogg </LOCATION> to the Silverhorn ski area in the <LOCATION> Silver </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Northern <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> remains a thick carpet of timber and once featured the largest stand of white pine in the world. <ORGANIZATION> Lumberjacks </ORGANIZATION> used to transport logs on the <LOCATION> Clearwater </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> to the sawmills of <LOCATION> Lewiston </LOCATION> in gigantic wooden flotillas complete with tents for cooking and sleeping. <ORGANIZATION> Lumberjacks </ORGANIZATION> will chop, saw and climb trees as <LOCATION> Lewiston </LOCATION> showcases its logging heritage with the grand finals of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Timber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sports </ORGANIZATION> in May, 1990. People from all races came to <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> to work the mines, farm or build the railroads. The centennial honors them all with celebrations or interpretive studies. In the midst of World War II in 1942, 9,400 Japanese-Americans were relocated to the wind-swept <ORGANIZATION> Minidoka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relocation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Twin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> in south-central <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. The Japanese <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> plans to build an interpretive center at the camp. Basques from the Spanish Pyrenees migrated to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from the 1800s on to tend sheep bands. <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION> is the largest enclave of Basques in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. They plan their second Jaialdi cultural festival in <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION> in June, 1990, drawing Basques from the West and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. When American explorers <PERSON> Meriwether </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> passed into <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> through <LOCATION> Lolo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pass </LOCATION> in 1805, they met friendly Shoshone and <PERSON> Nez </PERSON> <PERSON> Perce </PERSON> <PERSON> Indian </PERSON> tribes who had roamed through northern <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> on spotted appaloosa horses for centuries. They are two of the state's six tribes that will meet for the first time in <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION> on July 9-15 for an `` All Idaho Indian Expo'' to present their histories, dreams and social issues. The Idaho Centennial calendar lists more than 500 events next year, from an <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cowboy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poetry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gathering </ORGANIZATION> to a whistle stop tour of <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION>'s steam engine No. 8444. <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>'s Statehood Day celebration will run 43 hours from July 2 to Independence Day with a dizzying schedule of fireworks and parades `` Former Gov. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said ` I want a celebration of one million,'' meaning he wanted every man, woman and child involved,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said. `` We're coming as close to that as we can.''
