<BYLINE>By PRUDENCE HELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCARNO, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first tune the children of <LOCATION> Spruga </LOCATION> seem to learn is that of the klaxons of the yellow Postbuses that wind their way through the mountains above <LOCATION> Locarno </LOCATION>, at the northern end of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Maggiore </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Ticino </LOCATION>. A child on his tricycle pedals fast toward a stranger and stops just short of a collision. He sings out like a klaxon and pedals off. Another child, restless on her mother's lap, echoes the klaxon warning of the bus as it rounds a series of tight curves. Spruga, <PERSON> Indemini </PERSON> and their fellow communities wrapped high into the Alps above <LOCATION> Locarno </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lugano </LOCATION> or tucked into the river valleys are groupings of gray stone houses with heavy-looking, gray slate roofs. The gray, cobbled streets are often stairs. All look as if they had been, and would be, there forever. Geraniums and other flowers add a blast of color. <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> and pastures are all around and much of the year, a sound heard even more frequently than that of the klaxon is that of cowbells. At the foot of the mountains lie <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Maggiore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Locarno </LOCATION>, with palm and fig trees, oleanders and flowers and accessible lakefront. There are restaurants galore, an <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> and a <LOCATION> Lido </LOCATION>. On market day, booths along its main street sell everything from kitchen utensils to raincoats to jewelry made in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. The long arcade along the street is a sort of permanent market: sneakers and scarves, toys and teddy bears, and food of all kinds, including almonds that a smiling old lady dips in hot caramel. The arcade is a splendid shelter on a rainy day -LRB- <LOCATION> Locarno </LOCATION>, famous for its sunshine, does have rain, too -RRB-. Another indoor spot demanding a visit is the museum in the Castello Visconteo, a centuries-old restored castle whose exhibits range from <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Arp </PERSON>'s paintings to Roman glass, bronzes and other artifacts from the first century As one dines at the Trattoria da <PERSON> Luigi </PERSON>, takes the funicular to the shrine of the <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON>, or the lake boats to <LOCATION> Muralto </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Luino </PERSON> and the like, one sinks into the feeling of being in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. The names, the flowers, the sun, the blue water, the stuccoed buildings in pink and cream suggest the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. But it is <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, though the Swiss did n't get hold of it for keeps until the 16th century. <LOCATION> Locarno </LOCATION> was a commercial crossroads and military base under the Romans, who called the predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Celtic </ORGANIZATION> people they found there the <LOCATION> Helvetii </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Caesar </PERSON> defeated them in the Gallic Wars and then made allies of them. <LOCATION> Locarno </LOCATION> also was the scene in 1925 of an international conference including <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and a number of other nations that drew up a series of mutual guarantees known as the <LOCATION> Locarno </LOCATION> Pact, supposed to create a spirit of peace and goodwill. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s foreign secretary at the time, <PERSON> Austen </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON>, was a key figure at the meeting. <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> denounced the pact in 1936 and remilitarized the Rhineland. -LRB- <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON>'s half-brother, <LOCATION> Neville </LOCATION>, later <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> prime minister, signed another, more notorious peace pact with <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> in 1938 at <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> with similar results, with <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> as the pawn. -RRB- But the average visitor to <LOCATION> Locarno </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> <PERSON> Maggiore </PERSON> and its sister lake, <LOCATION> Lugano </LOCATION>, will probably save historical research for another time, concentrating instead on the lake boats and the mountains. Heading south from <LOCATION> Locarno </LOCATION>, he soon will truly be in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. On the way, he can stop at <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Brissago </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Isles </LOCATION>, where a botanical garden has plants from subtropical regions all over the world _ <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. This is just a foretaste of what's waiting at the south end of the lake, on <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Borromeo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, owned since the early 16th century by the <PERSON> Borromeo </PERSON> family _ prominent, rich and devout. -LRB- <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Borromeo </PERSON>, who died in 1584, was canonized. -RRB- The garden at <LOCATION> Isola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Madre </LOCATION> with its bitter orange, mimosa, Egyptian papyrus and banana trees has five terraces and a palace _ relatively modest by 18th century palatial standards. White and blue-green peacocks stroll the lawns and pheasants are almost under foot. On <PERSON> Isola </PERSON> <PERSON> Bella </PERSON>, the gardens are more elaborate: ten terraces, surmounted by a multistoried sculpture with niches containing figures and sculpted scallop shells. Statues are silhouetted against the sky. Atop the whole thing is the sculpted family symbol, a unicorn. It's baroque, beautiful _ and blatant. The enormous palace -LRB- one guidebook quotes French author <PERSON> Gustave </PERSON> <PERSON> Flaubert </PERSON> as saying it could have accommodated 2,000 people -RRB- is on a par with the gardens. There are a weapons and armor room, a tapestry gallery, a room where <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> and his family stayed as guests, and three theaters, including a Hell Theater, with marionettes symbolizing the environment and a two-pipe organ to produce lugubrious sounds. Lying between <PERSON> Isola </PERSON> <PERSON> Bella </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Isola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Madre </LOCATION> is <PERSON> Isola </PERSON> <PERSON> dei </PERSON> <PERSON> Pescatori </PERSON>, a longtime fishing village which has narrow streets and stone houses, but also a heavy overlay of tourists and vendors.
