ON> <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>'' -LRB- Reader's Digest -RRB- has maps, thumbnail sketches, and camping and access keys to attractions in the country close to exits on the interstate highway system. _ e for the Disabled,'' published by the non-profit charity, The Opening Door, contains information on accommodations, travel and services for the disabled. The <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> guide has state, national, Canadian and British distribution and is free to those with disabilities. Organizations are asked to reimburse the publisher $ 5 per guide. -LRB- The Opening Door, Route 2 Box 1805, <LOCATION> Woodford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>. 22580. -RRB- _ Warm-weather leisure destinations are the focus of a new group of travel guides from Bantam publishers. Two soft-cover trade-size entries cover <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and two pocket-size guides detail the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. _ A hefty guide to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> destinations is offered in `` Frommer's Dollarwise <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>,'' published by <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> and Schuster It breaks up the nation into seven regions and provides practical information on restaurants, accommodations, sights and excursions. _ <PERSON> Fodor </PERSON>'s reflects the fitness mood with a guide to `` Health and Fitness Vacations'' in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, listing health clubs and jogging trails. _ Business travelers to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are the market for a guide from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s The Economist magazine. `` <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s Business Cities'' focuses on 33 economic centers and provides information about local business services as well as dining, entertainment and sightseeing. _ Among numerous guide books to the sunny, warm <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> area is a new `` <LOCATION> Caribbean <