<SECOND>PM-Budget, Bjt,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Defense Reductions Will Do Little for 1991 Budget
Woes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Battle lines in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are already being drawn over whether and how to spend the money the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration plans to slice off next year's <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget. On one side are lawmakers who say liberalization in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> means the defense cuts should be large, and who want to use the money to beef up education, child care and other domestic programs that have been pinched in recent years. `` If the tearing down of the Berlin Wall means nothing more than we put the USS Missouri in <LOCATION> mothballs </LOCATION>, we will not have accomplished much,'' says liberal Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>. Arrayed against them are others who want to use the savings to reduce the 1991 deficit to $ 64 billion, a goal universally seen as difficult yet one that is required by the Gramm-Rudman balanced-budget law `` There seems hardly any room for discussion that the ... defense savings go to anything but deficit reduction,'' says Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.M. </LOCATION>, ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Dangling somewhere in between are senators and representatives who will be wary of defense cuts that affect military bases or contractors in their home districts. `` The light bulb in their heads says jobs,'' says <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Nissenbaum </PERSON>, a lobbyist for programs for low-income people. While <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> just finished its 1990 budget work on Nov. 22, the administration is already sketching out its spending blueprint for fiscal 1991, which begins next Oct. 1. That document will be presented to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Jan. 22. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> is reportedly preparing budget plans that will pare up to $ 180 billion from planned <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spending through 1994. Even if carried to the maximum, such cuts would reap little savings next year because of the nature of defense spending. In any given year, much of it is carried over from previous commitments _ such as an aircraft carrier on which construction began two years ago _ or is contained in difficult-to-break, long-term contracts stretching into the future. Even laying off troops brings with it offsetting expenses such as retirement payments, unemployment benefits and other costs. Because of that, the consensus among lawmakers and lobbyists is the reductions are likely to rein military spending by no more than $ 3 billion to $ 8 billion next year out of a nearly $ 300 billion Pentagon budget. The entire federal budget will be about $ 1.2 trillion. Such savings are but a tiny fraction of the $ 40 billion that many on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> expect will be needed to shave the 1991 deficit to the Gramm-Rudman target of $ 64 billion. `` The peace dividend is n't large, and there are a lot of claimants,'' says Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Minn </LOCATION>., ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Although the defense buildup of the early <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration years left a lasting public impression of an ever-growing <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, the military budget has shrunk over the last five years when the effects of inflation are considered. The trend was considered likely to continue in 1991 even before <LOCATION> Cheney </LOCATION> began considering reductions and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> European countries began asserting more political independence from the Soviet bloc. House Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., predicted `` a feeding frenzy'' last week by lawmakers eager to cut defense spending if the administration asks for a budget reduction But there's little question that the nation's defense system _ its bases and the companies that supply the weapons, food and other goods for them _ has a large base of support in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Even so, the need for deficit-reduction is likely to lead lawmakers to take a bite out of the military budget. The fight over reaching the Gramm-Rudman deficit target is likely to also focus on elements that have been contested in recent budget years: higher taxes, which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> opposes, and domestic cuts, which Democrats reject. `` A responsible budget approach has to be balanced,'' says Rep. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman, who has issued similar calls in the past with limited success
</TEXT>
