<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today left intact a $ 1.24 million award a leading accounting firm was ordered to pay to a water heater manufacturer. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Whinney </ORGANIZATION>, the accounting firm sued successfuly by <ORGANIZATION> Bradford-White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which makes water heaters at a <LOCATION> Middleville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, plant. Bradford-White, a <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> corporation, in 1981 bought out another water heater manufacturer, W.L. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Tenn </PERSON>. In connection with that deal, <PERSON> Bradford-White </PERSON> accused <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Whinney </LOCATION>, the accountants for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, of falsely reporting <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s financial condition. The accounting firm had reported <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was in financial trouble. But <PERSON> Bradford-White </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Whinney </ORGANIZATION> concealed just how bad matters were, and contended that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was on the verge of bankruptcy. The lawsuit alleged that <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Whinney </PERSON> violated federal and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> securities laws. Bradford-White was awarded $ 1.24 million by a federal jury in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. Bradford-White has offices in that city. A federal judge later overturned the award, ruling that the verdict was inconsisent with some of the jury's own finding. But the 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> reinstated the award last April. The appeals court said there might have been some inconsistencies, but there is no doubt the jury believed <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Whinney </ORGANIZATION> misstated <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s net worth. The appeals court also rejected the accounting firm's claim that <PERSON> Bradford-White </PERSON> waited too long to sue. <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Whinney </ORGANIZATION> waived any such claim at the trial and can not rely on it on appeal, the 3rd Circuit court said. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Whinney </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Bradford-White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 89-604.
