<HEAD>Industry Reports Weekly Production</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Domestic coal production totaled 16.1 million tons during the week ending Nov. 25, down 22 percent from the 20.6 million tons produced in the previous week because of the Thanksgiving holiday, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> coal industry produced 16.7 million tons in the same week last year, according to the department's <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> ranked first among the 27 coal-producing states during the week with 3.3 million tons produced. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> was second at 2.3 million tons and <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> was third at 2.25 million tons, the department said. Domestic coal production so far this year is 878.1 million tons, 5.5 percent above last year's production at this time, the agency said. The week's production accounts for bituminous and lignite coal.
