<HEAD>United Arab Emirates Rejects OPEC Quotas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> oil minister <PERSON> Mana </PERSON> <PERSON> Said </PERSON> <PERSON> Otaiba </PERSON> said Monday his country was ready to limit its oil output, but not to the extent demanded by the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> Exporting Countries. <PERSON> Otaiba </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> was willing to reduce its current output, which he put at 2.6 million barrels a day, to under 2 million during the first half of 1990. But he stressed it would not accept a quota of 1.094 million barrels a day assigned under an <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> pact, reached last week. He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> was willing to limit production to under 2 million barrels a day if the other <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> nations abide by their quotas. The 13 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members agreed last week to set their output ceiling at 22 million barrels a day. It left the quota for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>, which has not complied with its <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> quota over the past two years, unchanged. <PERSON> Otaiba </PERSON> also said he expects demand for <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> crude to exceed 23 million barrels a day in 1990, higher than the group's own demand estimates. He said continued economic growth should keep demand strong. Moreover, recent upheaval in eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> could help spur demand by touching off new economic growth there, he said.
