a vote.'' Nevertheless, airline industry analysts and stock-market investors speculated that the pieces of a new bid were falling rapidly into place. Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> told its employees on Friday that executives were working on a revised proposal for employee purchase of the airline company. `` It looks like they're really trying to put together a takeover deal here,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Kemper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The $ 300 a share offer from the pilots, <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> senior management and <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> fell through after the group failed to get the necessary financing. Since then, <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> stock has traded sharply lower. <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> figured the new deal would be for $ 210 to $ 240 a share. Another analyst said he had spoken with a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> pilot who `` threw out a $ 220 number.'' Analyst <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Buttrick </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said lenders who balked at and doomed the $ 300-a-share offer probably would agree to finance a deal at $ 225. <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> management is believed to be seeking strong commitments from lenders and the company's three major unions before announcing a revised buyout effort. The earlier pilot-management bid failed in October when lenders refused to finance it, citing the strong opposition of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union. The Machinists represent