<HEAD>IBM Calls Analyst Meeting Amid Rumors of Job Cuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf pvs to CORRECT 600 to 1,000, sted 6,000 to 1,000;
ADDS 1 graf with closing stock price.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> called a meeting for analysts Tuesday amid speculation that the company was going to announce job cuts and possibly one or more facility closings. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> declined to comment on the substance of the meeting but a spokesman indicated it would be important. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> has a 40-year tradition of no layoffs, and a senior <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> executive last week confirmed that the company would stick to that. However, if the company closed an operation such as a plant, office or distribution center, many employees might choose to quit rather than accept a transfer to a distant location. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> normally reduces employment by offering financial incentives to employees to quit or take early retirement. Earlier this year the company began its third such program in three years, hoping to trim 6,000 to 1,000 manufacturing jobs. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s stock rose $ 2.12 -LCB- a share to $ 99.25 Monday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The stock peaked at $ 175.87 -LCB- in August 1987.
