<HEAD>RESENDING FOR ALL NEEDING</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar finished mixed against major foreign currencies Monday as traders renewed their interest in the West German mark. Gold prices tumbled more than $ 12 an ounce, retreating after a strong advance recently. Traders said last week that bullion was getting overvalued and that such a drop was possible. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold for current delivery dropped $ 12.50 a troy ounce to $ 401.10. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> quoted a troy ounce of gold bullion at $ 401.20 as of 4 p.m. EST, $ 12.30 lower than Friday's late bid. <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Money </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> said currency dealers directed attention mainly to the West German mark and bought on speculation that the country will have to raise interest rates to stem a possible surge in economic growth. The Swiss franc was weighed down by heavy selling pressure related to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>'s lower interest rates compared with its European neighbors, particularly <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said. Trading in dollars is expected to be light this week ahead of Friday's potentially market-moving report on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment. A government report that said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factory orders fell 0.2 percent in October evoked little reaction among dollar traders although it reinforced the notion that economic growth is sluggish. Currency dealers overseas, meanwhile, were said to be closing out positions before the year end. Market volume tends to dry up toward the end of the year, when dealers are hesitant to risk profits or add to losses. Dealers also were expected to remain reluctant to trade heavily while they assess the outcome of the weekend's superpower summit and what it will mean for the future of the dollar and the world economy. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar rose to a closing 143.48 Japanese yen from 143.08 yen at Friday's close. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it rose further to 143.57 yen and, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar rose to 143.65 from 143.40 late Friday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fell to $ 1.5638 from $ 1.5665 late Friday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound fell to $ 1.56225 from $ 1.5625 late Friday. Other dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with Friday's late quotes included: 1.78425 West German marks, down from 1.7865; 1.6065 Swiss francs, up from 1.5995; 6.0915 French francs, down from 6.1020; 1,314.50 Italian lire, down from 1,316.50; and 1.16365 Canadian dollars, down from 1.6505. Selected late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late rates Friday were: 1.7808 West German marks, down from 1.7825; 1.5995 Swiss francs, up from 1.5925; 6.0800 French francs, down from 6.0875; 2.0095 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0150; 1,312.00 Italian lire, down from 1,313.25; and 1.1640 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1662. Precious metals prices declined in what dealers described as a technically motivated correction to a powerful runup. Gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 406.25 a troy ounce from $ 414 bid late Friday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the metal fell to a closing bid of $ 408 from $ 415 bid late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 2.79 to close at $ 409.31. Silver for current delivery slid to $ 5.509 a troy ounce from $ 5.663 on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex. Silver bullion fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 5.60 a troy ounce from $ 5.70 bid late Friday.
