<HEAD>Wall's Departure Unfair, But Not Surprising, Say Some Texans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>'s resignation Monday as the nation's chief thrift regulator came as no surprise in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, where much of the industry's problems have been centered Politicians and industry officials said they believed Wall had become a symbol of the industry's failings and, as such, had to be replaced as head of the Office of Thrift Supervision. Rep. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Republican who also serves on the <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> was part of the solution, not part of the problem.'' But <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> added, `` I think -LRB- the resignation -RRB- was inevitable. That's not to say it was fair.'' Although it was Wall's slowness in closing down <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> that was the catalyst for the current wave of criticism, <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> said, `` I think <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> would have been, even without <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, a controversial person because he was solving problems. `` He left the savings and loan industry stronger than when he came in,'' <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> said. Wall was chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> from July 1987 until last August, when its function as the federal regulator of the savings and loan industry was transferred to the new Office of Thrift Supervision. The <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> thrift landscape is much changed from Wall's <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plan </LOCATION>, devised last year to bring new capital into the industry. The mergers, designed to take advantage of tax laws before they expired on Dec. 31, 1988, have been criticized by some who complain the deals were too expensive. Under the plan, steel companies, home builders, investors and other non-traditional thrift owners bought up groups of insolvent institutions and packaged them into new entities. Four of the five largest <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> thrifts were created under the Southwest Plan. `` In the final accounting, which wo n't be done for several years, these <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plan </LOCATION> deals might look better than they do today, based on the cost of resolutions that the <ORGANIZATION> RTC </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is experiencing,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferguson </PERSON>, an industry consultant in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. `` I guess he had just taken about all the flak he could take,'' said H.R. `` Bum'' Bright, whose <ORGANIZATION> Bright </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banc </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> was seized by regulators earlier this year. `` We thought he had fundamentally a reasonable program on his original <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plan </ORGANIZATION>, one that would work out that would be less cost to the taxpayers than the subsequent plans appear to be from our standpoint.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pledger </PERSON>, commissioner of the Savings and <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> had the toughest job in government because of the magnitude of the problems.'' He praised <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>'s attempts to focus public attention on the healthy portion of the industry. `` He has been able to ... maintain a approach that recognizes that a large portion of the thrift industry is profitable and is doing well.''
