<HEAD>Florida Power Corp. Nuclear Plant Fined $50,000 by NRC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRYSTAL RIVER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has been fined $ 50,000 for allegedly failing to make sure safety equipment was up to standards at its <LOCATION> Crystal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> nuclear plant, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The alleged violations involved water pumps and valves that were of commercial quality and did n't meet federal specifications for nuclear safety equipment, said <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. In one case, the impeller of a backup pump used to bring in sea water for cooling had only five vanes instead of the required seven. `` For seven weeks, that pump was not capable of fulfilling its safety function,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said. The St. Petersburg-based utility, which has 30 days to either pay the fine or appeal it, has corrected all of the violations listed in the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> fine, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said. He said the alleged violations came as the utility was in the process of trying to upgrade its safety equipment to meet new, more stringent guidelines imposed by the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> last March. `` We were making an honest effort to meet federal guidelines within the window of direction we had from the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> said. The utility was fined $ 100,000 by the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> in September for the alleged inability of some safety equipment to operate under post-accident conditions, <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> said.
