<HEAD>Gaming Device Maker Sues Japanese Company for Patent Infringement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The No. 1 gaming device maker in the world filed a federal lawsuit Monday against a Japanese company, claiming the foreign firm is using three of the larger company's patents to make slot machines. International Game Technology filed the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sigma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sigma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Game </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Sparks </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, subsidiary that makes the slot machines. `` We believe that most if not all of Sigma's slot machines on the market infringe on our patents,'' said <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, representing Reno-based <ORGANIZATION> IGT </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Stefanik </PERSON>, director of operations for Sigma Game, said the company was unaware of the suit, which claims its slot machines are copies of patented <ORGANIZATION> IGT </ORGANIZATION> slot machines. `` Everybody uses these types of slot machines,'' <PERSON> Stefanik </PERSON> said. `` So their reasoning behind the lawsuit is beyond me.'' <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> IGT </ORGANIZATION> wants to force Sigma to change its slot machines so they do n't use patented IGT slot devices. <ORGANIZATION> IGT </ORGANIZATION> also seeks unspecified damages to compensate for any business the company might have lost because of the alleged patent infringement, <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said. `` These devices were patented for a reason _ because they have unique elements,'' <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> IGT </ORGANIZATION>, which had revenue of $ 140 million last year, has a similar lawsuit pending against a different Japanese company, <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, and its Nevada-based subsidiary company, Universal Distributing of <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> In that lawsuit, patent infringement is n't claimed, but <ORGANIZATION> IGT </ORGANIZATION> alleges Universal used <ORGANIZATION> IGT </ORGANIZATION>'s trade secrets in manufacturing a video poker game named `` Player's Edge.''
